column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: VERY SLOW LEAK FROM BOTTOM OF 55 GAL DRUM (PLASTIC).  DRUM WAS ON SKID. DRUM HAD A SCREW IN THE BOTTOM OF IT.  DRUM WAS PLACED ON SIDE THEN DIKED.

AFTER UNLOADING THE PRODUCT HOSE WAS DRAINED AND PLACED INTO HOSE TUBE FOR TRANSPORT.  IT APPEARS THAT THE HOSE STILL CONTAINED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT (EST.) 1/2 TO 3/4 OF A GALLON THAT LEAKED OUT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE'S DRIVEWAY.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: BAG PUNCTURED WITH FORKLIFT DURING LOADING PROCESS.  APPROXIMATELY 2 LBS LOST.  BAG WAS TAPED AND CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CAPTURED AND PREPARED FOR DISPOSAL.

THERE WAS A SMALL DENT IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WHICH THE MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM.  TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED IN FOR PROPER  CLEAN UP AND DECONTAMINATION.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN IN CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOR THE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER LEANED OVER TO GET SOFT DRINK BETWEEN SEATS, WHEN HE LOOKED UP HE SAW A DEER ON LEFT SIDE OF HIGHWAY.  MOVED TO RIGHT, DROPPING TIRES ON RIGHT SIDE OFF HIGHWAY ONTO SHOULDER.  THE SHOULDER SLOPES DOWNWARD TO A FIELD.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STEER RIG BACK ON HIGHWAY, BUT REAR OF TRAILER SLID DOWN SLOPE PULLING RIG OVER ONTO RIGHT SIDE.  AS RIG SKIDDED ON SIDE THE TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED AT SUPPORT RING AND SHELL OF TRAILER.  THE TRAILER RUPTURE DISC ALSO BLEW OUT.  HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM OFFLOADED PRODUCT FROM WRECKED TRAILER, UPRIGHTED AND REMOVED TRACTOR/TRAILER FROM SCENE. SOIL WAS REMOVED, MIXED WITH SODA ASH, RETURNED TO GROUND.  WEST VIRGINIA D. E. P. APPROVED REMEDIATION WORK.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: PASCHALL DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE.  NOTICED PRODUCT RUNNING OUT NOSE OF TRAILER.  TWO BARRELS WERE RUPTURED.  DRIVER STATED HE HAD TO MAKE AN EMERGENCY STOP AND BELIEVES THAT IS WHEN THE BARRELS RUPTURED CONSIGNEE DAMMED UP PRODUCT WITH DRY CHEMICAL AND DILUTED WITH WATER.  MOST OF PRODUCT WENT IN DRAIN AT END OF CONSIGNEE'S DRIVE.  EMI WAS CALLED AND SENT AES (AMERICAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE) TO CLEAN UP.  AES PUMPED UP 250 GALLONS DISCOVERED AFTER AES LEFT WAS ACCEPTED BY CONSIGNEE TO BE TAKEN TO THEIR DISPOSAL FACILITY.   DRIVER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR NEXT DISPATCH.
THE PACKAGE HAD A CRACKED CAP.  I PROCEEDED TO PROCESS AND DISPOSE OF THE PACKAGE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL  DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: WEARING PROPER PPE RESPONDED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE ON YELLOW BELT.  PACKAGE WAS WET BUT NOT LEAKING OUT SO RETURNED IT TO THE CAGE.  USING DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID SHEETS PROCESSED THE PACKAGE.  2 BOTTLES WERE PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM AND I WAS RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. DECONTAMINATED PPE AND FILLED OUT ALL PAPERWORK.

column168: FREIGHT WAS CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT.  CALLED INFOTRAC FOR MSDS.  CLEANED UP W/ KITTY LITTER & PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AT XPN.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: THE DELIVERING CARRIER (CSXT( WAS CONTACTED BY THE CAR SHIPPER.  THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE TANK CAR STARTED TO VENT PRODUCT VAPOR FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WHEN THE CAR WAS BEING UNLOADED.  THE CONSIGNEE CHECKED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR AND FOUND IT TO BE WELL BELOW THE PRV ACTIVATION PRESSURE, THE CONSIGNEE DETERMINED THAT THE PRV WAS MALFUNCTIONING.  THE CONSIGNEE APPLIED A "CHLORINE C KIT" CAP TO THE PRV WHICH STOPPED THE VAPOR BEING EMITTED FROM THE CAR.  AFTER THE CAR IS OFFLOADED THE PRV WILL BE CHANGED.  *NOTE: THE DELIVERING CARRIER (CSXT) IS MAKING THIS REPORT AS REQUIRED BY 49 CFR PART 171.6 AS THE CARRIER HAS KNOWLEDGE THAT THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  THE RAILCAR WAS NOT IN CSXT'S POSSESSION NOR WAS CSXT RESPONSIBLE FOR THE RELEASE THAT OCCURRED. NARRI=2(5+10)x(2+0)=60 CAUSE CODE = 417

THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: DURING UNLOADING AT THE CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS TERMINAL, DOCK WORKERS DISCOVERED THAT MOST OF THE 32 DRUMS OF THIS SHIPMENT HAD LEAKED AROUND THE DRUM LIDS, WHICH WERE OPEN TOPS, DURING TRANSIT DUE TO SLOSHING OF CORROSIVE LIQUID.  ONE DRUM HAD FAILED ON THE BOTTOM AND FORMED A SMALL LEAK ON THE CONCRETE DOCK.  CORRECTIVE ACTION INCLUDED CLEANING THE DOCK AND REPAINTING WITH AN EPOXY PAINT SEAL AND REMOVING ALL TRAILER FLOOR AND PANEL CONTAMINATED FROM THE RELEASE FOR DISPOSAL AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.  ALL 32 DRUMS OF PRODUCT WERE OVERPACKED, LABELED, AND SHIPPED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE SHIPPER WAS WARNED OF SHIPPING THE MATERIAL IN THESE DRUMS IN THE FUTURE TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING AGAIN.

A LIQUID WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM REAR TRAILER DOORS, AND UPON OPENING, SEVERAL CARTONS CONTAINING A DOT CORROSIVE LIQUID WERE FOUND TO HAVE BEEN CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT STACKED ON TOP OF THE MATERIAL WHICH HAD SPILLED. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND A HAZ MAT CONTRACTOR COMPLETED CLEAN UP.  WASTE MATERIAL WAS DRUMMED FOR OFF SITE DISPOSAL.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL IS NOT A RCRA REGULATED WASTE.

CUSTOMER WAS PREPARING TO UNLOAD THE CARGO TANK AND HAD MADE ALL NECESSARY CONNECTIONS AND SUPPLIED AIR TO THE CARGO TANK TO AIR TRANSFER THE LOAD. THE UNIT WAS PARKED IN THE UNLOADING AREA AND CONTAINMENT PAN WAS PLACED UNDER THE OUTLET VALVE. UPON OPENING THE EXTERNAL AND INTERNAL VALVE, THERE WAS A DRIP THAT STARTED BETWEEN THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES AT A FLANGE. THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS IMMEDIATELY HALTED, PANELS REMOVED TO EXPOSE THE FLANGE AND THE FLANGE WAS TIGHTENED DOWN SECURELY. UNLOADING WAS THEN COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. SPILLAGE WAS COLLECTED IN THE CONTAINMENT PAN AND PLACED INTO THEIR TREATMENT SYSTEM.

DRIVER WAS DELIVERING LTL FRT IN FLORENCE AL. HE OPENED HIS TRAILER DOOR AT ONE OF HIS STOPS AND NOTICED A SMELL AND STARTED LOOKING FOR THE PROBLEM. HE FOUND THE DRUM THAT WAS LEAKING IN NOSE OF TRAILER. A PALLET OF FRT HAD FELL ON TOP OF PAIL AND CAUSED A LEAK IN PAIL. DRIVER GOT THE PAIL AND SECURED IT SO IT WOULD NOT LEAK AND PUT OIL DRY ON SPOT WHERE IT HAD LEAKED TO ABSORB THE LIQUID. DRIVER PUT THE PAIL IN A PLASTIC GARBAGE BAD AND SENT IN A BOX TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKING.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: SWITCH CREW NOTICED LEAKING TANK CAR PRIOR TO DEPARTING STATION. CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED ON A CLEAR TRACK. MASON CITY FIRE WAS CONTACTED TO ASSIST IN CONTAINMENT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SEAL ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE CAUSING PRODUCT TO DRIP OUT. CAR OWNER CONTRACTED RESCAR OF CEDAR RAPIDS, IA, TO REPAIR CAR. HOWEVER, AFTER ASSESSMENT, IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE PRODUCT WOULD BE TRANSFERRED TO TRUCKS.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION TO OUR TERMINAL LOCATION, A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PAINT SEEPED OUT AROUND THE TOP SEAL OF THE DRUM. THE LID WAS TIGHTENED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AND THE DRUM WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.
DURING TRANSPORTATION TO THE CUSTOMER, THE LIDS BECAME LOOSE CAUSING SOME SEEPAGE. THE LIDS WERE TIGHTENED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AND THE CUSTOMER ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT.

TOTE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS. THE TOTE WAS EXAMINED AND NO EXTERNAL DAMAGE HAD OCCURRED, THE LEAK WHICH WAS VERY SLOW WAS EXITING A DEFECTIVE TOTE. THE TOTE WAS PLACED ON ANOTHER TRAILER WHICH HAD BEEN LINED WITH ABSORBANT AND SECLUDED IN OUR YARD. PLASTIC WAS ALSO PLACED UNDER THE UNIT FOR ADDED PROTECTION. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED PRIOR TO ANY HANDLING. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. THE MFG OF THE PRODUCT SENT TRIANGLE CHEM TO SCENE WITH AN OVERPACK TO PLACE THE TOTE INTO. THEY CARRIED THE TOTE TO THEIR LOCATION FOR APPARENT REPAIRS.

WHILE DRAWING A SAMPLE OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE DISCHARGE LINE ON THE CARGO TANK THE DRIVER FAILED TO FIRST CLOSE THE DISCHARGE VALVE BEFORE REMOVING THE PRODUCT LINE SECUREMENT CAP.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS.

USING THE SHIPPERS TRAILER, OUR DRIVER DISCOVERED TWO HOSES ONBOARD.  THERE SHOULD HAVE BEEN ONLY ONE.  HE CHOSE THE WRONG HOSE TO UNLOAD.  THE HOSE DEVELOPED A LEAK AND 2-3 GALLONS OF ACID WERE DISCHARGED.  THE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT AND HAS REMOVED ALL IMPROPER HOSES FROM THEIR TRAILERS.  IN ADDITION OUR DRIVER WAS DISCIPLINED AND ANY FURTHER INCIDENTS COULD RESULT IN TERMINATION.  WE HAVE A VERY THOROUGH TRAINING PROGRAM.  WE ALSO DON'T TAKE SPILLS LIGHTLY.  IN FACT WE WERE JUST RECOMMENDED FOR ISO 14001 CERTIFICATION.

column168: THE HOUSTON TRAILER ARRIVED IN GULFPORT ABOUT 8:15AM ON 5/4/01.  AFTER OPENING THE DOOR, OUR DOCK LEADMAN NOTICED THE DAMAGED BAGS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CALLED ME.  WE THEN CALLED OUR SAFETY FIELD REP AND HE ADVISED US TO SHUT THE DOOR AND NOT TO DO ANYTHING  WITH THIS TRAILER UNTIL HE CALLED US BACK. THE SAFETY REP FOR THE HOUSTON TERMINAL WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THE SPILL AND IS GOING TO INVESTIGATE THIS MATTER WHEN HE GETS BACK TO HOUSTON. OIL MOP OUT OF NEW ORLEANS WAS CALLED TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP. WE HAD 2BGS OF SODIUM NITRITE TORN OPEN AND 4BGS OF SODA ASH TORN OPEN.  THE DAMAGED BAGS  WERE PUT IN SALVAGE DRUMS BY OIL MOP.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CF TERMINAL IN FT. WORTH, PERSONNEL FOUND THAT A PAIL OF ADHESIVE MATERIAL HAD SPILLED DURING TRANSPORT AND LEAKED THROUGHOUT THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS PULLED AWAY FROM THE DOCK AREA AND A LOCAL SUBCONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  ONCE INSIDE THE TRAILER, THE SUBCONTRACTOR FOUND 1X5 GAL PAIL OF ADHESIVE HAD BEEN PUNCTURED DUE TO A PALLET HAVING BEEN PUSHED INTO THE PAIL.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE PAIL WERE LOST INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE SUBCONTRACTOR OFFLOADED THE FREIGHT AND CLEANED THE MATERIAL OFF OF THE TRAILER AND THE FREIGHT.  THE LEAKING PAIL WAS THEN PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK, ALONG WITH THE PPE AND ABSORBENTS USED BY THE SUBCONTRACTOR.  THIS PAIL WAS LEFT ON THE DOCK TO BE PICKED UP AT A LATER DATE.

THE PAIL HAD RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS AND THIS WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CF PERSONNEL.  THE PAIL WAS THEN PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK AND LEFT ON THE DOCK FOR DISPOSAL BY A LOCAL SUBCONTRACTOR.

column168: ON 05/03/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 1315 HOURS, WHILE CONDUCTING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE CN/IC BATON YARD, BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA, A SMALL AMOUNT OF LADING ESCAPED FROM THE MANWAY AREA ON RAIL TANK CAR TLDX 216008. A CN/IC SWITCHMAN STANDING ON THE GROUND NEAR-BY WAS SUBSEQUENTLY EXPOSED TO THE RESULTING MIST.  FIRST AID GIVEN, EMPLOYEE DID NOT WISH TO SEEK MEDICAL TREATMENT AND RETURNED TO WORK.  TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS PROTRUDING FROM BETWEEN THE MANWAY LID AND NOZZLE.  THE MANWAY EYEBOLTS APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN OVER TIGHTENED AND NOT IN SEQUENCE.  GASKET PROPERTY POSITIONED AND EYEBOLTS PROPERLY SECURED.  TANK CAR DECONED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION. NARRI=5(5+5+0)X(2+0)=100     CAUSE CODE = 208

DELIVERY HAD BEEN COMPLETED & DRIVER GOING BACK TO HIS TERMINAL. SITTING ON STATE SCALE, A PLUG IN ONE OF THE COMMODITY DELIVERY HOSES CAME OFF OF THE HOSE BEING CARRIED IN THE TRAILER HOSE TUBE, ALLOWING PRODUCT RESIDUE IN THE HOSE TO FALL ONTO THE SCALE.  A MATLACK RESPONSE TEAM FROM THEIR MEMPHIS TERMINAL RESPONDED & CLEANED UP THE SPILL, UNDER SUPERVISON OF SCALE PERSONNEL.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING ONE 200 GALLON PLASTIC TANK ENCASED IN AN ALUMINUM FRAME, THE TANK WAS PUNCTURED. A&D ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF ARCHDALE, NORTH CAROLINA RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  A&D ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES APPLIED OIL DRY TO THE REMAINING FREE PRODUCT AND USED A VACUUM TRUCK TO PUMP THE REMAINING LIQUID FROM THE DAMAGED TOTE TANK.  SEVEN (7) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF OIL DRY, AND FREE LIQUID WERE TRANSPORTED BY A&D ENVIRONMENTAL TO THEIR FACILITY IN ARCHDALE, NORTH CAROLINA FOR DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE THREE BAGS WHICH WERE PART OF A THIRTY-TWO BAG SHIPMENT BECAUSE OF RIPPED PACKAGING.  THE BAGS HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN NOTED DAMAGED WHEN RECEIVED AT THE DESTINATION TERMINAL FROM ANOTHER TERMINAL. ONE OF THE BAGS HAD BEEN RECOUPED AND REPAIRED WITH CLEAR TAPE AND TWO OTHER BAGS HAD SMALL TEARS IN THE PAPER BUT THE CONSIGNEE WOULD NOT ACCEPT THEM.  BAGS HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT IN TRANSIT.  DAMAGED BAGS HELD IN OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DOCK MAN DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  THE LOADING TERMINAL HAD PLACED A SHRINK WRAPPED SKID OF 9 PAILS ON TOP OF A 55 GAL. DRUM IN THE TRAILER.  THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE PLACED AROUND THE SKID TO PROPERLY BLOCK THE PAILS IN.  DURING TRANSIT THE SKID OF PAILS FLIPPED OVER OFF THE DRUM AND HIT THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE IMPACT POPPED THE LID LOOSE OF ONE PAIL WHICH CAUSED THE PAIL TO LOSE THE LIQUID CONTENTS.  THE DOCKMAN RESPONSIBLE FOR THE IMPROPER LOADING OF THE PAIL WILL RECEIVE CORRECTIVE ACTION FROM A SUPERVISOR.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING, PRODUCT ESCAPED THROUGH A HOLE IN THE VENT PIPE CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS TO BE LOST.  CLEANUP PERFORMED BY KENAN PERSONNEL WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT
EMPLOYEE UNLOADED WRONG COMPARTMENT OF TRAILER, CAUSING AN OVERFILL IN WHICH APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.  CLEANUP PERFORMED BY MARION ENVIRONMENTAL WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENTS
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, EMPLOYEE OVERFILLED TANK CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO BE LOST.  CLEANUP PERFORMED BY DEPT OF DEFENSE PERSONEL WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DURING UNLOADING AT THE CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS TERMINAL, A DOCK WORKER DRIVING A FORKLIFT PUNCTURED A 55 GALLON DRUM CONTAINING TETRAHYDROTHIOPHENE CAUSING A RELEASE INSIDE ONE OF THE TRAILERS.  ANOTHER WORKER MOVED THE DRUM TO ITS SIDE SO THE DRUM WOULD NOT LEAK ANYMORE. CORRECTIVE ACTION INCLUDED CLEANING THE TRAILER FLOOR AND OVERPACKING THE LEAKING DRUM INTO THE AN 85 GALLON OVERPACK.  THE RELEASE SENT TWO CF WORKERS TO THE HOSPITAL COMPLAINING OF NAUSEA AND THROAT PAINS.  THE EL PASO FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED THE CF WORKERS UNTIL THE SCENE WAS CONSIDERED UNDER CONTROL AND CLEAN.  THE DRUMS WAS DISPOSED OF HAZ A HAZARDOUS WASTE ALONG WITH ABSORBENT GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP.  THE DOCK WORKER WAS INSTRUCTED TO UTILIZE BETTER CAUTION WHILE UNLOADING DRUMS FROM THE TRAILERS IN THE FUTURE TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING AGAIN.

DURING LOADING AT ORIGINATING TERMINAL, DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT. MATERIAL CONTAINED IN NOSE OF VAN.  AREA ISOLATED AND CONTRACTOR BROUGHT IN TO OVERPACK LEAKING DRUM.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED.

ON 05/13/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 0915 HOURS, A CN/IC SWITCHMAN NOTICED A LIQUID SPLASH NEAR HIM FROM THE TOP OF RAIL TANK CAR UTLX 650026 DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE GEISMAR YARD, GEISMAR, L.A. TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT THE BOLTS TO THE BLIND FLANGE OF THE FILL HOLE COVER WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  COVER PROPERLY SECURED BY THE SHIPPER AND TANK CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

ON 05/08/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 1915 HOURS, WHILE CONDUCTING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE CN/IC ARGO/GATX YARD, ARGO, ILLINOIS TWO CN/IC TRAIN CREW MEMBERS REPORTED THAT THEY WERE EXPOSED TO THE VAPORS OF LIQUID PRODUCT COMING FROM RAIL TANK CAR ETCX 623047.  BOTH EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL MEDICAL CLINIC, EXAMINED AND RELEASED BACK TO FULL DUTY.  TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  GATX PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND FOUND BOLTS ON THE FILL HOLE COVER WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  FILL HOLE COVER BOLTS TOOL TIGHTENED BY GATX.  TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT. NARRI=5(5+1+0)X(2+2)=120  CAUSE CODE = 200

column168: OUR LOADED UNIT ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE TO UNLOAD, WHEN THE PLANT OPERATOR OPENED THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVE PRODUCT SPRAYED FROM THE THREE INCH CAMLOK FITTING ON THE DISCHARGE VALVE.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE CAMLOK FITTING WAS LOOSE.  WE REMOVED THE FITTING, RETAPED THE THREADS WITH TEFLON TAPE REPLACED THE CAMLOK FITTING AND UNLOADED THE TRAILER WITH NO PROBLEMS

OUR TRAILER HAD BEEN PRELOADED AND PLACED ON THE BAYTOWN TERMINAL YARD TO AWAIT FOR A ROAD DRIVER TO PICK IT UP.  A TERMINAL SHOP MECHANIC WAS WALKING THE LOAD LINE DOING A TRAILER CHECK WHEN HE NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER.  WE TRANSLOADED THE PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER TRAILER

column168: THE SHIPPER HAD JUST COMPLETED LOADING OUR TRAILER IN THERE PLANT.  THE OPERATOR WAS PLACING THE SEALS ON THE TRAILER WHEN HE NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TRAILER WAS NOT HOLDING.  THE PLANT UNLOADED OUR TRAILER PUTTING THE PRODUCT BACK INTO THEIR STORAGE TANK

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: THE DRIVER WAS AT A CUSTOMER SITE AND WAS LOADING A 30-GALLON STEEL DRUM ONTO HIS TRUCK.  HE INSPECTED THE DRUM AND FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM WAS CORRODING.  WHILE OVERPACKING THE DRUM INTO A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM, THE BOTTOM OF THE 30-GALLON DRUM PARTIALLY DETACHED AND SPILLED TWO GALLONS OF PAINT SLUDGE ONTO THE ASPHALT LOT.  THE DRIVER FINISHED OVERPACKING THE 30-GALLON DRUM AND PLACED ABSORBENT MATERIAL ONTO THE SPILLED PAINT.  THE WASTE ABSORBENT WAS PLACED INTO THE 55-GALLON DRUM ALONG WITH THE LEAKING DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURES NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A TRUCK WAS AT A TEN DAY TRANSFER FACILITY LOADED WITH DRUMS FROM A HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE COLLECTION THAT WAS TOOK PLACE OVER THE WEEKEND. ON MONDAY, THEY DISCOVERED HALF A GALLON OF PAINT WASTE ON THE ASPHALT LOT. IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK, ONE OF 55-GALLON DRUMS HAD DEVELOPED A PINHOLE LEAK SPILLING APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM AND ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ONTO THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE LEAKING 55-GALLON DRUM.  THE SPILL PROCEDURE APPROXIMATELY 75 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 300 CANAL STREET IN LAWRENCE, MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DIVER WAS COUNSELED ON DRUM INSPECTION AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: ON MAY 22, 2001, A TRUCK DRIVER OFFLOADED DIESEL FUEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK (AST) AT A BIZZACK CONSTRUCTION SITE NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF HIGHWAY 80 AND MORTON BOULEVARD IN HAZARD, KENTUCKY.  A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF RED DYE DIESEL FUEL OCCURRED WHEN THE HOSE WAS UNHOOKED FROM THE AST AFTER AN APPARENT OVERFILL.  ENVIROPRO, A LOCAL CONTRACTOR, WAS ASKED TO RESPOND ON IMPERIAL TRANSPORT'S BEHALF. PRIOR TO AND UPON THEIR ARRIVAL, ABSORBENTS WERE APPLIED TO THE SPILL AREA. ENVIROPRO REPLACED ABSORBENTS AS NEEDED AND PREPARED SPENT ABSORBENTS FOR DISPOSAL.  PONDED WATER IN THE VICINITY OF THE AST WAS AFFECTED BY THE SPILL.  NO STORM DRAINS OR STREAMS WERE AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE.  THE KENTUCKY DEPARTMENT FOR ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WAS MADE AWARE OF ALL ACTIVITIES.

column168: DOUBLE STACKED  PALLETS OF PAILS FROM ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER. NO PALLETS OR CARD-BOARD USED TO SEPARATE SKIDS OR BRACE THEM FROM MOVEMENT IN TRAILER. LOADING ERROR REPORT WAS SENT TO LOADING TERMINAL AND CHEMICAL INCIDENT REPORT WAS COMPLETED. EMPTY PAILS HAVE BEEN PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AND SPILLED CLEANED UP. WILL ADVISE ALL PERSONAL THAT LOAD TRAILERS TO NOT DOUBLE STACK SKIDS OF PAILS AND TO ENSURE THAT ALL SUCH SHIPMENTS ARE BRACED TO PREVENT FUTURE ACCIDENTS.

column168: NATX 91038, LOAD OF CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE, WAS REPORTED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S EXPORT YARD IN JACKSONVILLE, FL THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER RESPONDED. IT WAS FIRST DISCOVERED THAT 2 OF 8 MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LESS THAN HAND TIGHT. THE PLUG ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WAS ALSO LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED BY CSXT. THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED TO INSPECT THE MANYWAY GASKET AND FOUND THAT THERE WAS NO MANWAY GASKET PRESENT. THE CONSIGNEE, MILLENNIUM SPECIALTY CHEMICAL WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND TO INSTALL A GASKET. MILLENNIUM PERSONNEL INSTALLED A TEMPORARY GASKET OF TEFLON ROPE, THE MANWAY COVER WAS SECURED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED. CSXT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC. THE INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED WITH A MR STEVE RATLIFF WITH GAYLORD.HE INDICATED HE WOULD INVESTIGATE. NARRI: 5(5+1+0)X(2+0)=60 CAUSE CODE:207

USLX 21214, LOAD OF TURPENTINE, WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S EXPORT YARD IN JACKSONVILLE, FL. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER RESPONDED. THE CAR WAS FIRST FOUND TO HAVE 3 OF 8 MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED TO INSPECTED THE GASKET. THE GASKET WAS MADE OF TEFLON ROPE AND WAS BROKEN IN TWO PLACES WITH PART OF GASKET HANGING DOWN INSIDE THE MANWAY NOZZLE. THE CONSIGNEE, MILLENNIUM SPECIALTY CHEMICAL, WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND TO REPLACE THE GASKET. MILLENNIUM PERSONNEL INSTALLED A TEMPORARY GASKET MADE OF TEFLON ROPE. THEY SECURED THE MANWAY COVER AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED. NARRI: 5(5+1+0)X(2+0)=60 CAUSE CODE:209

GATX 43277, LOAD OF CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE, WAS REPORTED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S EXPORT YARD IN JACKSONVILLE, FL THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER RESPONDED. IT WAS FIRST DISCOVERED THAT 1 OF 8 MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WAS LESS THAN HAND TIGHT. THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE OK. THE MANWAY COVER WAS SECURED WRENCH TIGHT. IT WAS THEN DISCOVERED THAT THE PIPE NIPPLE THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS ATTACHED TO WAS CORRODED THROUGH WHERE THE NIPPLE WAS WELDED TO THE TOP OF THE TANK LEAVING A 1/2 IN. WIDE BY 5 IN. LONG HOLE IN THE NIPPLE. THE CONSIGNEE, MILLENNIUM SPECIALTY CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND. MILLENNIUM PERSONNEL USED AN EPOXY METAL PUTTY TO PLUG AND PATCH THE HOLE IN THE PIPE NIPPLE. MILLENNIUM OBTAINED AN FRA SPECIAL MOVEMENT AUTHORITY (FRA-0105108) TO MOVE THE CAR INTO THEIR FACILITY FOR UNLOADING. NARRI: 2(5+3+0)X(2+0)=32 CAUSE CODE: 662

TANK CAR GATX300478 WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE TOP AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN MEMPHIS, TN. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER CONTACTED. THE SHIPPER CONTRACTED AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, FERGUSON HARBOUR, TO RESPOND AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS THE CONTRACTOR FOUND A LEAK BETWEEN THE FLANGE ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE AND THE LIQUID VALVE. 1/2 INCH, GORTEX ROPPING MATERIAL WAS USED AROUND THE FLANGE TO SEAL AND SECURE THE LEAKING AREA. THE CAR WAS SECURED AND MOVED A SHORT DISTANCE TO THE CONSIGNEE SO THAT IT COULD BE UNLOADED. NARR: 5(5+7+0)X(2)=120 CODE: 293

TANK CAR HAS 2 PRD'S, BOTH 75 PSI. THE "A" END PRD WAS DISCHARGING CONSTANTLY. PRESSURE READING OF THE CAR INDICATED APPROX. 1 PSIG. AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO REVERSE THE "O" RINGS TO STOP THE LEAK, BUT THE RINGS WERE IN NO CONDITION TO BE REVERSED. A PIECE OF THE "O" RING WAS DETECTABLE AT THE EDGE OF THE RETAINING CAP. PRD WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR RE-BLANKETED WITH NITROGEN TO RETURN TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION. NARR=5(4+5+0)X(2+0)=90 CAUSE CODE=414

UTLX 130328 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ON SIDES OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, REACT ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE MANWAY COVER GASKET STOPPING THE RELEASE.

ADMX 30480 WAS INVOLVED IN A YARD DERAILMENT WHERE THE CAR REMAINED ON IT'S WHEELS WITH THE CAR LEAKING AT APPROXIMATELY 35 DEGREES. DURING RERAILING OPERATIONS A DRIP OF PRODUCT WAS NOTED FROM THE VACUM RELIEF VALVE ON TOP OF THE CAR. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED AROUND THE VALVE TO CONTAIN THE LEAKAGE. WHEN THE CAR WAS UPRIGHTED THE LEAK STOPPED. NO DAMAGE TO THE TANK SHELL OR VALVES.

GATX 27419 NOTED EMITTING VAPORS STEADILY BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED AND FOUND THE REULATOR VALVE FROZEN IN OPEN POSITION DUE TO ICE BUILD-UP DURING NORMAL VENTING. ICE WAS REMOVED AND VALVE RESEALED.

UTLX 46928 NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. CARRIER MECHANICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND FOUND THE LEAK COMING FROM WHERE THE LIQUID EDUCATION VALVE THREADS ONTO THE FLANGE. THE VALVE WAS REMOVED, THE THREADS CLEANED AND TEFLON TAPE APPLIED TO THE THREADS. THE VALVE WAS PLACED BACK ON THE FLANGE PROPERLY TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: GATX 90412 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ON TO OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, FERGUSON-HARBOR, RESPONDED AND FOUND LOOSE VALVE SECUREMENT BOLTS AND A DEFECTIVE GASKET ON THE LIQUID EDUCATION VALVE FLANGE. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE BOLTS PROPERLY TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE.

GATX 10841 WAS NOTED WITH LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA BY A PRIVATE CITIZEN AT A GRADE CROSSING. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED, LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND FOUND THE LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE CAR WAS WHICH HAD CONDENSED ON THE CAR AND WAS DRIPPING OFF THE BOTTOM OUTLET. THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE FEDERAL REGULATORY REQUIREMENT TO REPORT ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENTS INVOLVING AN EVACUATION. DUE TO THIS INCIDENT APPROXIMATELY 15 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM AN AREA LOGGING CAMP. NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE RELEASED.

CELX 23118 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ON SIDE OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, PETROCLEAN SERVICES AND RESCAR, RESPONDED AND FOUND A LEAK BETWEEN THE LIQUID LINE VALVE AND THE VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE DUE TO A DETERIORATED GASKET. THE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND A NEW GASKET INSTALLED STOPPING THE RELEASE.

RCRX 1019 WAS NOTED EMITTING PRODUCT FROM TOP OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, FERGUSON-HARBOUR, RESPONDED AND FOUND MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE DURING SWITCHING.  THE DEFECTIVE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW VALVE STOPPING THE RELEASE.

column42: TARS, LIQUID INCLUDING ROAD OILS AND CUTBACK BITUMENS
column168: MLSU 124287, A 20 FOOT INTERMODAL TANK CONTAINER, WAS NOTED WITH PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE DRAINAGE TUBE LOCATED ON TOP OF THE CONTAINER WHEN THE TANK WAS MOVED.  THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, BOASSO COMPANY, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS MISSING ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE DURING MOVEMENT.  A GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE COVER PROPERLY CLOSED AND FASTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE.  CC=210 5(5+3+0) X (2+0)=80

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING TWO, ONE GALLON METAL PAILS WAS DISCOVERED IN THE THIRD QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE PAILS WAS DAMAGED AND THE OTHER WAS AFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY HALF A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT BEING LOADED ON TOP. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT TOWELS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON, AFFECTED PAIL AND DAMAGED PAIL WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING TWO CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE PUNCTURED BY THE FORKLIFT AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT SIX BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING TWO BOTTLES WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY SIX GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, SIX DAMAGED BOTTLES AND TWO DAMAGED CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TWENTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, FORTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO UNAFFECTED BOTTLES WERE RECOUPED AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED FIFTY POUND PAPER BAGS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY THREE CUPS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE BAGS WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, A DUSTPAN AND A BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT AND ONE OF THE DAMAGED PAPER BAGS WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE OTHER DAMAGED PAPER BAG WAS TAPED UP AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON THE DOCK, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THREE LEAKING, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS.  APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DRUMS WERE LEAKING DUE TO CRACKED BUNGS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, BOOTIES, GOGGLES, AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE BUNGS ON THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE REPLACED AND THE DRUMS WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE, THREE HUNDRED TWENTY-FIVE GALLON TOTE TANK WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT THE 1/2 WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A CRACKED BREATHING TUBE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS. ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON, CONTAINING FOUR, FOUR LITER METAL CANS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE ONE-THIRD MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE METAL CAN WAS LEAKING AND THE REMAINING THREE WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY TWO TABLESPOONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE CARTON.  THE FREE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED BY THE STYRAFORM SURROUNDING THE METAL CANS IN THE CARTONS. THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF A LOOSE CAP.  THE SAN FRANCISCO FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE CAP ON THE METAL CAN.  THE LEAKING METAL CAN AND THREE UNAFFECTED CANS WERE PLACED INTO A NINETY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  ONE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE MATERIAL AND NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS SOUGHT.

THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT CAUSING THE PAIL TO FALL AGAINST OTHER FREIGHT AND DENTING THE SEAM.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED AN INVESTIGATION USING GLOVES AND GOGGLES.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE GLOVES AND GOGGLES WERE PLACED INTO THE TERMINAL WASTE RECEPTACLE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING, ONE FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM IN A SHIPMENT OF FORTY WAS PUNCTURED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED LEVEL "C" PROTECTION, NEUTRALIZER, ABSORBENT PILLOWS AND BOOMS, BROOMS AND SHOVELS TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  THE DAMAGED FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM, ABSORBENT PILLOWS AND ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SECOND FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND TWO FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. FORKLIFT OPERATOR RAN FORK THRU DRUM. 1 GALLON OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID PRODUCT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CLEANUP SMALL AREA IMPACTED ON CEMENT DOCK. DAMAGED DRUM AND CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT WERE PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUM. DRUM WAS PLACED IN SECURED AREA PENDING DISPOSAL.

AFTER THE 5- GAL PAIL OF MATERIAL WAS UNLOADED FROM THE TRAILER AND SET ON THE DOCK AREA, THE PAIL WAS STRUCK BY A "TOW MOTOR" AS DESCRIBED BY MR. JOE HRABUSA OF CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON WAS RELEASED ONTO DOCK AREA. CF PERSONNEL PLACED OIL DRY ABSORBENTS ON THE LIQUID AND THEN VACATED THE AREA DUE TO THE STRONG ODOR ASSOCIATED WITH THE LIQUID. HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS THEN CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE REST F THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE OIL DRY. THIS WAS THEN PLACED INTO A POLY DRUM AND LEFT ON SITE TO AWAIT DISPOSAL. THE DISPOSAL WILL BE ARRANGED BY ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT INC.

TWO CARDBOARD BOXES  CONTAINING ACETONE AND ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL WERE FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED ONTO THE CARDBOARD CONTAINER, BUT NOT ENOUGH TO HAVE LEAKED ANY ONTO THE FLOOR. EXACT REASON FOR THE LEAK IS UNKNOWN BUT IT IS ASSUMED THAT IT WAS BECAUSE OF EITHER THE CARTONS HAD BEEN CRUSHED OR THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIALS JUST LEAKED INSIDE THE CARTONS. THE CARTONS WILL BE PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SENT BACK TO THE MANUFACTURE.

ON 5-01-01 A DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID WAS RUPTURED WHEN IT WAS HIT WITH A FORKLIFT ON THE DOCK AT THE CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS TERMINAL IN JOLIET, ILLINOIS. CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS NOTIFIED E.M.I. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL, TRANSPORTED IT OFF SITE FOR FURTHER DISPOSAL. EMI JOB# 10457
DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO ABOVE GROUND TANK. 50 GALLONS OVERFLOWED AND RAN INTO CONTAINMENT. CUSTOMER SAID WAS THEIR RESPONSIBILITY. TANK REPORTEDLY WOULD HOLD LOAD.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON TUESDAY MAY 8, 2001, A MARISOL DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN ON TO BROAD STREET FROM PLEASANT VIEW TERRACE WHEN HE REALIZED THE TOP SAFETY VALVE VENT WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED. DRIVER PULLED TRUCK OVER, CLIMBED UP TO CLOSE VENT AND REALIZED ABOUT A HALF GALLON OF MATERIAL SPILLED OUT INTO TOP CATCH BASIN AND DOWN THE DRAIN PIPE. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP MATERIAL IN TOP CATCH BASIN AND UNDERNEATH TANK WAGON WITH ABSORBENT RAGS. TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS, DRIVER HAS BEEN RETRAINED IN LOADING AND UNLOADING TANK WAGON PROCEDURES.

UPON DOING AN EQUIPMENT CHECK, DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID DRIPING FROM TRAILER, HE PUT BUCKET UNDER TO CONTAIN SPILL ALSO USED ABSORBENT, SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED WHO SENT A CLEAN UP CREW TO CLEAN UP ALL CONTAMIATION OVERPAC LEAKING DRUM CLEAN TRAILER AND RELEASE TRUCK TO COMPLETE DELIVERY.

WHILE MAKING EQUIPMENT CHECKS DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID SPILLING FROM TRAILER DRIVER CONTAINED AS BEST HE COULD CONTACTED STATE DEQ OPERATOR #4, CONTACTED HAZMAT CLEAN UP CREW ALL WASTE WAS CLEANED UP AND TAKEN TO FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. THE PARKING AREA WAS CONTAMINATED AND WAS DUG UP AND DISPOSED OF AND PARKING AREA WAS REPAVED.

PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE SOLVENT HOSE ON THE NOSELINE. THE RUBBER SEAT IN THE MAIN VALVE WAS DISLODGE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SEEP INTO THE NOSELINE. INCIDENT WAS CLEANED UP BY MARCOR (410-742-6161) ON THE SAME DATE AND TANKER WAS RETURNED TO TERMINAL FOR REPAIRS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON 05/18/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 1505 HOURS, WHILE SEPARATING ENGINES FROM THEIR TRAIN CONSIST IN ST. GABRIEL, LOUISIANA, A CN/IC TRAIN CREW MEMBER NOTICIED LANDING SLOSHING FROM THE VENT AREA ON TOP OF RAIL TANK CAR FPAX 931130. ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. CN/IC AND SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED, NOTING THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED ALLOWING LADING TO ESCAPE. FRANGIBLE DISC REPLACED, TANK CAR DECONNED AND MOVED TO THE CN/IC GEISMAR YARD. ONCE AT THE GEISMAR YARD, THE TANK CAR WAS TAKEN TO THE SCALE AND FOUND TO BE 2,500 LBS OVERWEIGHT. SHIPPER ARRANGED THE OFF LOADING OF LADING TO UNDER 263,00 LBS. TANKCAR THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT NARRI=5(5+5+0)x(2+0)=100 CAUSE CODE=441/419

ON 05/19/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS, A CN/IC SWITCHMAN NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM THE TOP OF RAIL TANK CAR UTLX 650026 DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE GEISMAR YARD, GEISMAR, LA. TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED. SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT THE BOLTS TO THE BLIND FLANGE OF THE DIP TUBE WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT. DIP TUBE PROPERLY SECURED BY THE SHIPPER, TANK CAR DECONED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT NARR 5(5+5+0)X(2+0)=100 CAUSE CODE=467

column168: GATX 49527 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ON TOP OF CAR DURING INBOUND INTERCHANGE INSPECTION BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, BUNCHER RAILCAR SERVICES, RESPONDED AND REPLACED A RUPTURED SAFETY VENT FRANGIBLE DISC STOPPING THE RELEASE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. FOUR LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK PRIOR TO LOADING AT THE TERMINAL. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED DUE TO LOOSE BUNGS. THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZER. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION AT THE TERMINAL. THE BUNGS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE DRUMS CONTINUED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE AT THE BNSF RAILYARD IN FORT WORTH, TX, FREE PRODUCT  WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM ONE DAMAGED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DRUM WAS CRUSHED DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT WHICH CAUSED THE DRUM TO CRACK AT THE TOP SEAM. HAZMAT ONE OLATHE, KS WAS NOTIFIED TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP. THE FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENTS. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS SEALED WITH CLAY. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED DRUM WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO AN EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM. THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS FORWARDED TO THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, FORT WORTH TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED WITH PUTTY AND PLACED INTO A SIXTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM WHICH IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH UNDAMAGED BOTTLES. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

FOUND THIS FREIGHT IN TEMPORARY STORAGE HOLD WITH TWO BAGS LEAKING.  THE BAGS WERE LOADED ON CORRUGATED PALLETS AND WERE OVERHANGING THE.  TWO FACTORS ATTRIBUTED TO THE UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF TWO BAGS.  #1.  ONE  BAG THAT WAS OVERHANGING THE PALLET APPARENTLY WAS STRUCK BY OTHER FREIGHT STAGED BEHIND IT.  #2.  ONE OF THE CORRUGATED PALLETS THAT THIS FREIGHT WAS STACKED ONTO COLLAPSED UNDER THE WEIGHT OF THE SHIPMENT SUBSEQUENTLY CAUSING ONE OF THE BAGS TO RIP. PERSONALLY, I DO NOT FEEL THAT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGED IN PAPER BAGS SHOULD BE ALLOWED TO BE SHIPPED ON CORRUGATED PALLETS OR SHOULD BE ALLOWED TO OVERHANG PALLETS.  ALSO, IN MY OPINION I DO NOT FEEL THAT SOMETHING THAT IS IDENTIFIED AS A TOXIC HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE SHOULD BE SHIPPED IN PAPER BAGS REGARDLESS OF THE PACKAGING GROUP.  MANUFACTURERS SHOULD PUT THESE KINDS OF MATERIALS IN BETTER QUALITY PACKAGES THAT CAN WITHSTAND THE RIGORS AND THE HAZARDS ASSOCIATED WITH TRANSPORTATION.  AGAIN THIS IS JUST MY OPINION.

THE RESULTING IMPACT RUPTURED THE FIRST COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER AT THE TANK SHELL LANDING GEAR JUNCTURE RESULTING IN GASOLINE SPILLING DIRECTLY ONTO THE CARS RUNNING ENGINE THE BENETO DRIVER REMOVED ALL FOUR OCCUPANTS FROM THE CAR AND TURNED OFF THE CAR ENGINE BEFORE CALLING DISPATCH. DISPATCH THEN MAKE ALL THE APPROPRIATE PHONE CALLS. AN INCIDENT INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED WITH THE DRIVER TERMINAL MANAGER LPS STEWARD AND ANOTHER DRIVER. THAT INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE ROOT CAUSE WAS THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE EXHIBITED EXCESSIVE SPEED AND FAILED TO FOLLOW SAFE DRIVING PRACTICES. THE SOLUTION OF HOW TO PREVENT INCIDENT FROM REOCCURRING, WAS TO REINFORCE TO BENETO DRIVE THE PRACTICES. THE SOLUTION OF HOW TO PREVENT INCIDENT FROM REOCCURRING, WAS TO REINFORCE TO BENETO DRIVER THE NECESSITY TO CONSIDER OTHER DRIVER UNSAFE DRIVING HABITS WHEN MANEUVERING THE TRUCK. ALSO THE LPS STEWARD WILL CONVEY TO OTHER BENETO DRIVERS THE CIRCUMSTANCES OF THE ACCIDENT (VIA AN LPS BULLETIN) TO INCREASE DRIVER'S AWARENESS.

THE DRIVER HAD AIR UNLOADED 41,280 LBS. FROM THE CARGO TANK TO THE CONSIGNEES STORAGE TANK. THE STORAGE TANK WAS LOCATED ON THE 2ND FLOOR AND 75 FEET BACK INTO THE PLANT. THE DRIVER WAS UNAWARE OF ANY TYPE OF RELEASE. THE CONSIGNEE CALLED LATER IN THE DAY AND INFORMED OUR TERMINAL. THE CONSIGNEE CONTAINED, CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF THE PRODUCT.

THE INTERMODAL WAS STAGED ON THE GROUND AT THE YARD AND IT CONTAINED HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID N.O.S. THE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING FROM THE LOWER SEAL. CHESI PERSONNEL OPENED THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER AND REMOVED DEBRIS FROM THE BACK OF THE CONTAINER. THE INTERMODAL WAS MOVED FROM  ITS LOCATION AND THE  ALL THE IMPACTED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INSIDE THE INTERMODAL IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN 10 GALLONS OF LIQUID LEAKED FROM THE INTERMODAL

column168: CARRIER OFFICIALS FIRST BECAME AWARE OF THE 5/2/01 INCIDENT ON 5/17/01. THE FOLLOWING DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS IS BASED UPON PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION BY THE CARRIER: CARRIER'S DRIVER PICKED UP THE LOAD AS DESCRIBED ON THE ATTACHED MANIFEST ("EXHIBIT B") FROM VOPAK USA, WAYNE WV FOR TRANSPORTATION TO A DISPOSAL FACILITY IN EAST LIVERPOOL, OH. THE VOLUME OF CARGO WAS MEASURED AND THE VEHICLE AND ITS TANK WERE INSPECTED AND PROPERLY CHECKED AFTER LOADING BY THE DRIVER AND CONFIRMED BY EMPLOYEES OF SHIPPER. DURING TRANSPORTATION THE DRIVER USED I-64 EASTBOUND, AND TRAVELED THROUGH A ROAD CONSTRUCTION AREA BETWEEN INSTITUTE, WV AND DUNBAR, WV, A DISTANCE OF APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES. IN CHARLESTON, WV, ALSO ON I-64 EASTBOUND AND APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES FROM THE CONSTRUCTION AREA, THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL LEAKAGE FROM THE VEHICLE'S TANK. THE TRUCK WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY AND INSPECTED BY THE DRIVER, WHO FOUND THAT ONE OF THE WING-BOLT CLOSURE DEVICES ON THE TANK HAD LOOSENED, POSSIBLY FROM VIBRATION FROM THE ROADWAY. THE WING-BOLT CLOSURE DEVICE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO PAKERSBURG, WV, WHERE THE TRUCK WAS PARKED FOR THE NIGHT. FROM CHARLESTON, WV TO PARKERSBURG, WV, APPROXIMATELY 87 MILES, THE DRIVER MADE THREE STOPS TO FURTHER INSPECT THE WING-BOLT CLOSURE DEVICES TO INSURE THERE WAS NO FURTHER LEAKAGE FROM THE TANK. THE VEHICLE'S TANK HAD BEEN INSPECTED AND RECERTIFIED ON MARCH 8, 2001 BY TRANSPORT TANK TRAILER SERVICES, INC., BELPRE, OH, DOT NUMBER CT033 PER THE ATTACHED INSPECTION REPORT. ("EXHIBIT C"). AS PREVIOUSLY STATED OUT INVESTIGATION IS ONGOING AND DAMAGE CLAIMS, INCLUDING CLEANUP, ARE INCOMPLETE AS OF THIS DATE. ADDITIONAL AMOUNTS ARE EXPECTED TO BE MINIMAL.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS BEING UNLOADED OUT OF AN INBOUND AIRCRAFT WHEN FUMES AND SMOKE ALERTED HANDLING PERSONEL TO A PROBLEM.  THE SUSPECT PACKAGE EXHIBITED SMOKE FUMES AND A BURN HOLE ON ITS SIDE.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL TWO SIX POUND ELECTRIC STORAGE BATTERIES.  PER THE HMR THESE ITEMS ARE NOT REGULATED PROVIDED THAT THE OFFERING PARTY HAS GONE TO GREAT LENGTHS TO ENSURE THAT THE TERMINALS ARE PROTECTED FROM SHORT CIRCUIT.  THIS OBVIOUSLY DID NOT HAPPEN AND THE BATTERY ARCHED CAUSING A SMALL FIRE.  THE ITEM WAS CONTAINED AND HELD FOR F.A.A. INVESTIGATION.

THE TRAILER TIRES HIT A RAISED DRIVE WAY, WHICH MADE THE FUEL TO SLOSH WHICH CAUSED TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO OVERTURN, AND CAUSING THE WELD (SEAM) TO BUST CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT OF THE #1 COMPARTMENT.  THE DIESEL LEAKED OUT AROUND THE MANHOLE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: WHILE ENROUTE TO GARLAND, TX FOR DELIVERY, THE DRIVER VENTURED TOO FAR TO THE RIGHT DURING A LANE CHANGE.  AS A RESULT, THE DRIVER WENT OFF OF THE RIGHT SHOULDER.  DUE TO THE PREVIOUS RAINS IN THE AREA, THE GROUND ADJACENT TO SHOULDER WAS SOFT.  AS THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO MOVE BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY, THE VEHICLE DID NOT RESPOND, THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO TURN THE WHEEL LEFT.  EVENTUALLY, THE STEERING TIRES GRABBED AND MOVED THE UNIT TO THE LEFT RESULTING IN A ROLLOVER.  THE UNIT BLOCKED MOST OF THE TRAVELED PART OF THE ROADWAY, ANOTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING SOME DISTANCE BEHIND OUR UNIT STATED HE COULD NOT SEE THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE BLOCKING THE ROADWAY AND STRUCK OUR VEHICLE IN THE TRANSMISSION AREA.  BOTH DRIVERS WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL, OUR DRIVER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED, THE OTHER DRIVER WAS ADMITTED FOR SEVERAL DAYS.  RESPONDERS INCLUDED:  TRIMAC PERSONNEL (MARSHALL, TX), TEXAS HIGHWAY PATROL, KILGORE FIRE DEPT. BIG D HAZ-MAT HANDLED THE CONTAINMENT AND REMEDIATION OF THE SITE, BOB LONDON & SON TOOK CARE OF RIGHTING AND TOWING THE VEHICLE AWAY.  ONCE THE SCENE WAS SECURE, AND THE LEAK STOPPED, THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED AWAY.  INCREASE AWARENESS THROUGH MEETINGS AND CONVERSATIONS WITH DRIVER.

A SHIPMENT OF WASTE BEING LOADED INTO A TRAILER AT A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY.  THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS MOVING A DRUM FROM THE WAREHOUSE STORAGE AREA TO A TRAILER WHEN HE PUNCTURED THE 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM WITH THE FORKS.  THIRTY GALLONS OF A POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION SPILLED INTO THE WAREHOUSE'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED INTO STEEL DRUMS.  THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 400 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET IN LINDEN, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER FORKLIFT HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER WAS LOADING HIS TRUCK AT A CUSTOMER SITE.  HE DROPPED A POLY DRUM ONTO THE ASPHALT AREA AND THE TOP OF THE DRUM CRACKED NEAR THE LID. APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF WASTE TRICHLOROETHYOLENE SPILLED OUT.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 30-GALLON STEEL DRUM.  THE GENERATED WASTE WAS ALSO PLACED INTO THE STEEL DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 80 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 2120 SOUTH YALE STREET IN SANTA ANA, CA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER WAS LOADING HIS TRUCK AT A CUSTOMER SITE.  HE WAS MOVING A POLY DRUM THAT HAD INCORRECTLY CLOSED LID.  ONE QUART OF THE WASTE TETRACHLOROETHYLENE SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE AREA WHERE THE TRUCK WAS PARKED. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO THE DRUM.  THE LID WAS CORRECTLY RESECURED AND THE DRUM LOADED ONTO THE TRUCK.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3454 WOMACK ROAD IN ORANGE, TX FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A TRAILER WAS BEING OFF LOADED AT A TEN DAY WASTE ACCUMULATION CENTER.  THE WASTE IN THE TRAILER WAS TO BE OFF LOADED AND TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER HEADING FOR THE APPROPRIATE DESIGNATED DISPOSAL FACILITY.  WHILE BEING UNLOADED, A WRANGLER BAG WHICH IS A WOVEN PLASTIC FIBER CONTAINER LOOKED LIKE IT CONTAINED MORE THAN THE SOLID MATERIAL THE WASTE WAS PROFILED AS.  WHEN THE BAG WAS PLACED IN THE STORAGE AREA OF THE WAREHOUSE, LIQUID BEGAN TO LEAK OUT AND APPROPRIATELY ONE QUART OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE MATERIAL INSIDE THE WRANGLER BAG WAS REPACKED INTO 3X55-GALLON STEEL DRUM FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE WRANGLER BAG AND GENERATED WASTE ALSO PACKED INTO THE 55-GALLON DRUMS.  THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD IN DENTON, TX FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE ORIGINAL WASTE PICK UP WAS COUNSELED ON MATERIAL INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: TANK CAR UTLX 15965 WAS BEING MOVED INTO THE CSX MT. CLARE YARD AS PART OF TRAIN Q40628 WHEN A RAILROAD EMPLOYEE ON AN ADJACENT TRACK OBSERVED LIQUID COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR. THE TRAIN WAS SAFELY BROUGHT TO A STOP AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED. INSPECTION OF UTLX 15965 REVEALED THAT THERE WAS A BREACH (HOLE) IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK SHELL IN THE  AREA NEAR THE LIQUID EDUCTION SUMP PLATE. THE HOLE WAS APPROXIMATELY 3/8" IN DIAMETER AND APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED DUE TO CORROSION OF THE TANK SHELL. LIQUID PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM THE HOLE AND WAS COLLECTING UNDERNEATH THE CAR. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM AND CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER WERE ABLE TO SLOW THE LEAK BY PLUGGING THE HOLE. THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED AND SEPARATED FROM THE TRAIN AT A LOCATION WHERE THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR COULD BE TRANSFERRED. A SECOND TANK CAR, TGAX141545, WAS BROUGHT TO THE SITE AND THE CONTENTS OF UTLX15965 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TGAX141545. THE TRANSFER WAS CONDUCTED BY THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT (MDE). THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED IN PLACE BY THE RAILROAD'S CONTRACTOR UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF MDE, ONCE EMPTIED, UTLX 15965 WAS STENCILLED "LEAKY TANK-DO NOT LOAD" AND WAS MOVED TO A REPAIR SHOP UNDER FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY "FRA-0105110". TGAX141545 WAS TAKEN TO THE ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE FOR OFFLOADING. NARR: 2(5+3+0)X(4+0)=62 CAUSE CODE =647

ON MAY 28, 2001, AN AMERICA WEST AIRLINES STOCK CLERK IN PHX MATERIAL HANDLING WAS PREPARING A SHIPMENT OF OXYGEN BOTTLES TO BE SHIPPED TO ASTO-AIRE IN OAK FOR TESTING AND REPAIR.  IN PREPARING THE BOTTLES FOR SHIPMENT, HE REMOVED THE FITTING THAT IS LEFT OF THE GAUGE TO DRAIN THE REMAINING OXYGEN.  HE LEFT THE BOTTLES FOR A PERIOD OF TIME,  THEN REINSTALLED THE REMOVED FITTING AND PROCEEDED TO PACKAGE THE BOTTLES FOR SHIPMENT.  THE COMBINED SHIPMENT CONTAINED A TOTAL OF SIX BOTTLES - THREE 114CF BOTTLES AND THREE 11CF BOTTLES.  THE THREE 11CF BOTTLES WERE NOT EMPTIED BECAUSE THE PROPER FITTING WAS NOT REMOVED.  EFFORTS INITIATED TO PREVENT REOCCURENCE:  ALL OXYGEN BOTTLE SHIPMENTS BEING TRANSPORTED BY AIR WILL BE RE-INSPECTED BY A SECOND FUNCTION SPECIFIC STOCK CLERK PRIOR TO PACKAGING.  BOTH EMPLOYEES WILL SIGN OFF THE WAYBILL INDICATING THAT THE BOTTLES HAVE BEEN INSPECTED AND ARE CONFIRMED TO BE EMPTY.

BNSF TRAIN STOPPED ON MAIN TRACK WITH 3 OF 6 TRAILERS/CONTAINERS ON A INTERMODAL FLATCAR ON FIRE.  LOCAL F.D. EXTINGUISHED FIRE, BUT NOT BEFORE TWO TRAILERS AND ONE CONTAINER WERE DESTROYED IN TOTAL, INCLUDING CONTENTS. DURING FIRE RESPONSE, VEHICLE TRAFFIC ON STATE HIGHWAY 10 (WHICH PARALLELS TRACKS) WAS DETOURED FOR 2 1/2 HOURS.  CONTRACTED FIRE INVESTIGATORS DETERMINED THAT THE FIE ORIGINATED IN THIS TRAILER YFSZ 35837 AND SPREAD TO THE TWO ADJACENT INTERMODAL CONTAINERS (FSTU 625310 TO THE WEST & YFSZ 118897 TO THE EAST).  ALSO SEE DOT 5800.  1 REPORTS, BNSF INCIDENT NUMBER 01-0510-01B & C.  FIRE INVESTIGATION CONCLUDED THAT LARGE HEAVY ENGINE BLOCKS THAT WERE LOADED ATOP LIGHTER PACKAGED COMMODITIES EITHER CRUSHED OR FELL OVER ONTO THEM CAUSING DAMAGE TO PLASTIC BOTTLES OF NON-HAZARDOUS CHEMICAL COMPOUNDS OF CONSUMER VARIETY (PAINT RELATED TYPE MATERIALS, PAINT THINNERS); COMBUSTION FOLLOWED FROM THE SPILLED CHEMICAL MIXTURE.  THE LOAD SHIFT OF THE ENGINE BLOCKS IS ATTRIBUTABLE TO IMPROPER LOADING OF TRAILER BY SHIPPER AND THEY HAVE BEEN COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING PRACTICES.  BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR CLEANED DEBRIS & SENT IT TO APPROVED LANDFILLS: SOLID WASTE TO SUPERIOR FCR LANDFILL @ BUFFALO, MN & LIQUID WASTE TO EOG ENVIRONMENTAL @ MILWAUKEE, WI.

FORKLIFT PUNCTURE CAUSED RELEASE.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING TWELVE, 946.3 ML METAL CANS WERE DISCOVERED.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE 946.3 ML CAN WAS DAMAGED, AND FOUR 946.3 ML CANS WERE AFFECTED, AND THE REMAINDER WAS UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY 200 ML OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND WERE CONTAINED WITHIN THE CARTON.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS AS A RESULT OF A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT.  BAX GLOBAL INC.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PLACED THE CARTON AND THE TWELVE 946.3 ML METAL CANS INTO AN 85 - GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  THE 85 - GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM REMAINS AT THE BAX GLOBAL INC. FACILITY IN SWANTON, OHIO FOR DISPOSAL COORDINATION WITH SAFETY KLEEN.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CARGO TANK WHILE STOPPED AT A REST AREA.  DRIVER TOOK ACTION TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER AND CALLED THE CARRIER FOR ASSISTANCE.  OHIO DOT WAS NOTIFIED AND DID RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  THE REST AREA WAS CLOSED FROM 0930 TO 1430.  DURING THIS TIME ANOTHER CARGO TANK WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE AND THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE LEAKING TANK WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  PRODUCT THAT DRIPPED ON THE GROUND WAS CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND SUBSEQUENTLY ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH PROPER MEANS. CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A CRACK THAT HAD DEVELOPED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK NEAR THE FRONT.  NO SPECIFIC REASON FOR THE CRACK DEVELOPING COULD BE DETERMINED.

THE DRIVER CHECKED IN WITH THE RECEIVING DEPT. AND GAVE THEM THE SHIPPERS BILL OF LADING SHOWING THE SHIPPING NAME AND AMOUNT.  THE UNLOADER SIGNED OUR PAPERS OK TO UNLOAD.  THE DRIVER HAD PUMPED OFF APPROXIMATELY 98 %. WHEN THEIR STORAGE TANK OVER FLOWED INTO A DYKE AREA .  THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND NOTIFIED THE UNLOADERS.  THEN THEY DRUMMED OFF APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS INTO THE DRUMS.  ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND WILL BE CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF BY THE CONSIGNEE.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: RMCC REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE YARD AT EAGLE PASS, TEXAS. INSPECTION OF THE GAMX 5189 REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND HINGE ASSEMBLY WERE MISSING FROM THE CAR.  THE MANWAY WAS DISCOVERED LATER THAT DAY IN THE YARD.  INSPECTION OF THE HINGE ASSEMBLY REVEALED A CRACK IN THE WELDED RING THAT FIT OVER THE NOZZLE OF THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS A LOAD AND HAD TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO FIVE TRUCKS TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION. CELANESE HAS DECIDED TO RETIRE THIS PARTICULAR SERIES GAMX CARS AS THEY ARE CURRENTLY 34 YEARS OLD.

REPORTED LEAKING TANK CAR AT VOILA YARD IN CORPUS CHRISTI, TEXAS. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TWO OF THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE OUT OF PLACE WHICH CAUSED THE CAR TO LEAK WHEN SWITCHED.  THE BOLTS WERE SECURED AND THE CAR WAS CLEANED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

SFTZ 230519 WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT SOSAN YARD IN SAN ANTONIO, TEXAS. INSPECTION REVEALED TWO DRUMS IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER WERE LEAKING FROM CRACKS IN THE BOTTOM HEADS.  THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TRAILER REDZ 232565.  THE TWO LEAKING DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND ALSO LOADED INTO THE TRAILER AND THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  THE FLATCAR WAS PRESSURE WASHED AND RELOADED AND RELEASED.  THE CONTAMINATED TRAILER WAS HELD FOR DECONTAMINATED.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: A SHIPMENT OF PLASTIC BOTTLES CONTAINING  OVEN CLEANER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT THE POUGHKEEPSIE REGIONAL HUB.  A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  WASTE MATERIALS WERE STAGED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CAPS APPEARED TO NOT HAVE SEALED PROPERLY ON THE OVEN CLEANER BOTTLES.

SKID WEIGHING 830 LBS WAS LOADED ON TOP OF SKID OF HAZARD MATERIAL.  THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE USED BETWEEN THE TWO NOR WAS THERE A LOAD BAR USED TO BRACE THE LOAD THERE ALSO WAS NO DUNNAGE USED TO SURROUND THE FREIGHT FOR PROTECTION.  THE CAUSE OF THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING BY DSR.

85 CYLINDERS WERE LOADED IN THE NOSE OF TLR 313-6462 THE SAFETY CAPS ON THE TWO CYLINDERS THAT LEAKED WERE LOOSE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND NOTIFIED THE SAFETY CAPS WERE LOOSE & LEAKING AND ALSO THAT SEVERAL OF THE STEEL CYLINDERS WERE OLD AND TAGGED "OUT DATED". column168: AS THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING NORTHBOUND ON AIRPORT WAY SOUTH HE NOTICED THAT HIS TRAILER TIRES WERE WET. ARRIVING AT PSC BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL INC (PSC) THE TRUCK WAS BROUGHT INTO THE FACILITY AND IMMEDIATELY OFFLOADED TO FIND THE LEAKING CONTAINER.  PSC IS A HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY AND ALL EMPLOYEES ARE TRAINED IN SPILL RESPONSE.  THE FAILED CONTAINER WAS NEAR THE BACK OF THE TRAILER SO WITHIN MINUTES OF ARRIVAL THE FAILED CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED. THE DRUM WAS FOUND TO HAVE A HOLE IN IT AT THE 18-INCH MARK (APPROX. 31 GAL LEVEL). AT THIS TIME THE DRUM STILL CONTAINED 26 INCHES OF PRODUCT APPROX. 45 GAL). column168: DRIVER WENT TO SLEEP. VEHICLE RAN OFF THE LEFT HAND SIDE OF ROAD AND OVER TURNED IN A SAND BANK. NO PRODUCT SPILLED. DRIVER UNHURT. ROAD CLOSED, TRAFFIC REROUTED TO ALLOW WRECKER TO UPRIGHT VEHICLE

VEHICLE WAS TURNING ONTO FM626 WHEN LOAD SHIFTED.  IMPACT WITH SIDEWALL OF VAN CAUSED 110 GALLON CONTAINER TO CRACK SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 69 OF 110 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ALONG ROADWAY AND ONTO PROPERTY AT DESTINATION. APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE OF ROAD SURFACE WAS IMPACTED.  UNDER GUIDANCE OF TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCES CONSERVATION COMMISSION AND THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, AFFECTED AREAS OF ROADWAY, DITCH AND DESTINATION PROPERTY WERE REMOVED AND REPAIRED OR REPLACED.  REMOVED SOILS AND ASPHALT WERE DISPOSED OF AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE, IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATIONS, AT THE COVEL GARDENS LANDFILL IN SAN ANTONIO, TEXAS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE TO DELIVER FIVE CARTONS ON ONE SHIPPER'S SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET. THERE WAS LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR THAT HAD COME FROM ONE OF THE CARTONS. THERE IS NO OUTWARD SIGN OF DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGE. DRIVER STATED THAT HE HAD SEEN THE SHIPMENT PRIOR TO DEPARTING THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, AND THAT THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE APPARENT AT THAT TIME. HE DID NOT OBSERVE ANY LEAKAGE AT ANOTHER STOP AN HOUR BEFORE HE ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE. CONSIGNEE'S DOCK PERSONNEL GAVE THE DRIVER SOME OIL DRY TO SOAK UP THE STANDING LIQUID. THEY WOULD NOT UNLOAD THE SHIPMENT, NOR WOULD THEY LET THE DRIVER LEAVE BEFORE THE TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED. CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC AND ENGAGED A SPILL CONTRACTOR FOR A RESPONSE. CHEMTREC FAXED AN M.S.D.S. CONTRACTOR DISPATCHED A CREW OF TWO TECHNICIANS TO HANDLE THE SITUATION. A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER CALLED TO STATE THAT SHE WOULD BE SENDING A SEPARATE CLEAN UP INSTRUCTION SHEET THAT WOULD BE NEEDED IN ADDITION TO THE M.S.D.S. THE CONTRACTOR'S TECHNICIANS CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH THE PRESCRIBED SOLUTION. ONE CARTON HAD BEEN SHIPPED LYING ON ITS SIDE. THE CLOSURE OF ONE CAN IN THAT CARTON HAD PARTIALLY OPENED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF SOME CONTENTS. THE MATERIAL HAD WETTED ONE OTHER CARTON ON THE PALLET. THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE TWO WET/LEAKING CARTONS. THEY WERE PLACED  INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR RETURN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DEBRIS WERE PUT INTO ANOTHER DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS APPROACHING AN INTERSECTION DURING INCLEMENT WEATHER CONDITIONS. ACCORDING TO WITNESSES AND MECHANICS AFTER THE FACT, IT APPEARS THAT THE TRAILER BRAKES FAILED TO OPERATE PROPERLY (WOULD NOT RELEASE). THIS RESULTED IN THE UNIT ROLLING OVER ONTO THE HIGHWAY RIGHT OF WAY. CLEAN-UP OF APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF FUEL AND TRANSFER OF REMAINING LOAD WAS CONDUCTED BY : AUSTIN FIRE DEPT. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNIT; AUSTIN, TX; EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND ENVIRONMENTAL 9747 COBB, SAN ANTONIO, TX 78217; AND MISSION PETROLEUM CARRIERS, 8450 MOSELY RD. HOUSTON, TX 77287. THE TRAILER WAS A TOTAL LOSS AND DONATED TO THE AUSTIN FIRE DEPT. FOR TRAINING.

I. MODE OF TRANSPORTATION: PIPELINE  IX.  ON THURSDAY, MAY 10, 2001 BUCKEYE PIPE LINE COMPANY PURGED A SECTION OF ITS PIPELINE WITH NITROGEN TO CONDUCT REPAIR PROCEDURES.  ON FRIDAY, MAY 11, 2001 BUCKEYE PIPE LINE COMPANY STARTED REFILL OPERATIONS.  AT 0630 ON SATURDAY, MAY 12, 2001 A TANKER/VACUUM TRUCK WAS OVERFLOWED WHILE DISPLACING THE NITROGEN DURING THE REFILL OPERATION.  A BUCKEYE PIPE LINE COMPANY EMPLOYEE ON SITE CALLED TO HAVE THE REFILLED OPERATION SHUT DOWN, AND OPENED A MAINLINE VALVE TO DIVERT FLOW AWAY FROM THE TANKER/VACUUM TRUCK.  THE EMPLOYEE THEN CLOSED A 2" VALVE ON A 101 FITTING LOCATED ON THE MAINLINE, THEREBY ISOLATING THE TANKER/VACUUM TRUCK FROM THE MAINLINE AND STOPPING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE. PURGE AND REFILL PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH BUCKEYE PIPE LINE COMPANY EMPLOYEES THAT WERE INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT.  A SAFETY BULLETIN WAS ISSUED THROUGHOUT THE COMPANY REVIEWING THIS INCIDENT AND STRESSING PREVENTIVE MEASURES.

column168: CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON I-20 NEAR FOREST, MISS. WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED SPRAY COMING OFF THE REAR OF TRAILER. HE ENTERED THE REST AREA AT MILEPOST 90 TO INVESTIGATE. HE STATED WHEN HE OPENED THE TRAILER HE WAS DRIVEN BACK BY A POWERFUL AMMONIA ODOR. DRIVER WAS ABLE TO PUT HIS SPILL KIT AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND ON THE GROUND WHERE THE LIQUID WAS LEAKING. WHILE THE DRIVER WAS INVESTIGATING A SHERIFF'S DEPUTY ON PATROL CAME ON THE SCENE. THE DEPUTY NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND CHEM TREC. THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE CARRIER'S ON-CALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN. BASED ON THE ODOR AND THE MANIFEST THE TECHNICIAN WAS ABLE TO IDENTIFY THE LEAKAGE AS THE HUNTSMAN SHIPMENT.  THE CARRIER ENGAGED A CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE SITE AND MITIGATE THE INCIDENT.  THE TECHNICIAN OBTAINED AND FORWARDED THE PRODUCT'S  MSDS TO THE CONTRACTOR. HE ALSO ESTABLISHED CONTACT WITH A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, ALONG WITH ITS CHIEF WHO ALSO SERVES AS THE COUNTY'S EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY COORDINATOR ARRIVED.  THEY MADE INITIAL ENTRY IN SCBA INTO THE TRAILER. WHILE THERE THEY SPREAD ABSORBENT TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE FROM THE TRAILER. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE STATE ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCY AND TO EPA REGION IV. EPA DUTY OFFICER HAD AN ERRONEOUS REPORT THAT THE CARRIER'S DRIVER HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED FROM THE SITE. ON-SCENE EMS DID SURVEY THE DRIVER'S VITAL SIGNS BUT HE DECLINED ANY FURTHER TREATMENT. HE CONTINUED WORKING WITHOUT LOST TIME AND HAS SUFFERED NO ILL EFFECTS SINCE. THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AND MADE THEIR ASSESSMENT. THEY FOUND THAT THE DAMAGE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A CRACK IN A DENT AT THE BOTTOM. THE DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN STRUCK BY A FORK OR SOME OTHER OBJECT. THEY PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND SPREAD ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THEY PERFORMED SITE MITIGATION AS DIRECTED BY LOCAL OFFICIALS. THE CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS RELEASED AND CONTINUED TO ITS DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN THE SALVAGE DRUM.

A SINGLE, UNPALLETIZED DRUM FROM COATES SHIPMENT WAS SECURED TO THE TRAILER WALL NEAR THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER. IN ORDER TO ACCESS THEIR SHIPMENT, THE FIRST STOP HAD TO MOVE THAT SINGLE COATES DRUM. DRIVER REPORTED THAT THERE IS NOTHING IN THE FLOOR THAT WOULD HAVE DAMAGED THE DRUM.

ON ARRIVAL AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP, THE DRIVER OBSERVED WHAT APPEARED TO BE RED PAINT ON ONE OF HIS TWO TRAILERS. HE CHECKED INSIDE THE TRAILER AND SAW THE SAME MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. NONE OF IT WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER AT THE MOMENT BUT THE WAS CONCERNED THAT MOVING THE TRAILER MIGHT CAUSE IT TO START LEAKING. THE FACILITY PERSONNEL ASSISTED THE DRIVER TO LOCATE, IDENTIFY AND SECURE A LEAKING DRUM OF XYLENE SOLUTION. THE DRIVER THEN SEPARATED HIS TRAILERS AND BACKED INTO THE FACILITY'S DOCK SO THAT THEY COULD UNLOAD THEIR SHIPMENT. CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE A NEARBY CONTRACTOR OVERPACK THE LEAKING PAIL AND CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE. THE CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE PAIL AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM A FAILED BOTTOM CHIME.

column168: DURING UNLOADING OF THE PICK UP TRAILER AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM A CRACK IN ITS BOTTOM.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND THE FAILED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

AT A LOCAL CARTAGE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED WITH LIQUID ON ITS HEAD.  THE LIQUID WAS DETERMINED TO BE COMING FROM THE DRUM'S BUNG, BUT ONLY WHEN THE DRUM WAS SUBJECTED TO MOTION.  NO LIQUID HAD PROGRESSED PAST THE HEAD.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE.  THEY WILL PROVIDE A NEW BUNG AND INSTRUCTIONS FOR REPLACEMENT.

DOCK REPORT INDICATES THAT THE DRUM ARRIVED AT J1 ON A BROKEN PALLET. WHILE THE UNLOADER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK THE PALLET UP WITH A FORK TRUCK, A FORK STRUCK AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  DOCK PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE AND OVERPACKED THE DRUM.  IT WAS HELD PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FIRST OF MULTIPLE STOPS, THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED A PUNGENT SULFUR-LIKE ODOR EMANATING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE ALSO SAW WHITE POWDER LYING ON THE FLOOR.  CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED ONE DRUM WITH A FORKBLADE PUNCTURE AT THE VERY BOTTOM.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE SITUATION TO THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT.  CARRIER INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO PULL AWAY FROM THE DOCK DOOR, STAY AWAY FROM ANY BUILDINGS OR VEHICLES, LEAVE THE TRAILER DOOR SHUT AND AWAIT A SPILL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR'S ARRIVAL.  CARRIER CONTACTED CHEMTREC TO OBTAIN A MSDS AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE HAZARD OF THE MATERIAL RELATIVE TO A SMALL AMOUNT OF WATER COULD CAUSE A CHEMICAL REACTION THAT WOULD GENERATE ENOUGH HEAT TO CREATE A VERY HOT BURNING FIRE.  THE WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE DAMP AND MISTY BUT NOT RAINING.  CARRIER ENGAGED THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR, PROVIDING THEM WITH AN MSDS AND TECHNICAL ADVICE FROM THE SHIPPER.  CARRIER ALSO NOTIFIED LOCAL AUTHORITIES, REQUESTING RESPONSE TO THE SITE OF FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS.  BASED ON INFORMATION AT HAND, THE CONTRACTOR MADE INITIAL ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER IN LEVEL "B" PPE.  PRIOR TO THE CONTRACTOR'S ENTRY THE POLICE DEPARTMENT CLOSED THE ROAD AT THE SITE.  THEY ALSO EVACUATED A CONVENIENCE STORE AND A BEAUTY PARLOR. AFTER ENTRY AND ASSESSMENT, THE CONTRACTOR ISOLATED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND OVERPACKED IT.  THE CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE AND NEUTRALIZED THE MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL.  ONCE DONE, THE INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED. INVESTIGATION DISCLOSED THAT THE SHIPMENT IMMEDIATELY BEHIND THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS ON SHORT PALLETS AND THAT STANDARD FORK BLADES WOULD EXTEND BEYOND THE PALLET.

VAN TRUCK WAS DRIVING TOWARD CONSIGNEE ADDRESS WHEN A PEELED TIRE GOT TANGLED UP IN THE RIGHT REAR AXLE. THE PEELED TIRE BEGAN TO RUB AGAINST THE AXLE AND THE HIGHWAY AND THE ENSUING FRICTION LED TO A FIRE BREAKING ON THE REAR OF THE VAN. THE FIRE BURNED THE VAN AND MELTED THE ALUMINUM FRAME. THE INTENSITY OF THE HEAT CAUSED TO TOPS OF TWO DRUMS TO BURST. THE REMAINING DRUMS PLASTIC LINERS MELTED; CONTAMINATED THE LIQUID PRODUCT AND IT COULD NOT BE USED. OHKA  AMERICA CALLED ECO-LOGICAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO ARRANGE FOR SITE CLEAN-UP AND DISPOSAL.  ENCLOSED WITH THIS REPORT IS THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST, CERTIFICATE OF DISPOSAL AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE REPORT.

column168: TRUCK WAS SOUTHBOUND WHEN THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED.  RIGHT SIDE TIRES TRAVELLED ONTO SHOULDER (SHOULDER IS VERY NARROW, NOT PAVEMENT INTO DIRT) WHEN DRIVER CORRECTED THE PUP TRAILER ROLLED OVER ON THE SOFT DIRT AND ROLLED INTO DITCH.  DRIVER CALLED EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER AND THEY CALLED BAKER FIRE DEPT. WHO DIKED SPILL.  PETRO COMP SUPERVISED CLEANUP AND SOIL TESTING.  ALL CONTAMINATION HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM SITE.

TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON US 59, SOUTH OF DIBOLL, TX AND DRIVER APPARENTLY FEEL ASLEEP AND DROVE OFF THE HIGHWAY INTO THE DITCH. VEHICLE RAN INTO AND OVER A CULVERT. SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE VACUUM DEVISE. SHIPMENT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS AT THE SITE, TRANSFERRED THE LOAD AND MADE APPROPRIATE CLEAN UP EFFORT. DRIVER WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE AND TRANSPORTED TO A LUFKIN, TX HOSPITAL. HE WAS HELD OVER NIGHT FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED THE NEXT DAY INJURIES WERE NOT HAZ-MAT RELATED. DRIVER NOT WEARING SEAT BELT. TRACTOR WAS HEAVILY DAMAGED AND TOTALED. CARGO TANK DAMAGES WERE MODERATE WITH NO DAMAGE TO THE BARREL. CARGO TANK REPAIRED, HM-183 INSPECTIONS UPDATED AND PLACED BACK IN SERVICE.

column168: THE WEATHER AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT WAS CLOUDY, RAINY AND DARK. DUE TO THESE CONDITIONS THE DRIVER DID NOT SEE THE SECTION OF US 59 VEERED SLIGHTLY DUE TO RECENT IMPROVEMENTS. FEARING THAT HE HAD RUN OFF THE ROAD HE OVER CORRECTED, LOOSING CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND THEREBY CAUSING THE ROLL OVER. THE AREA WAS DIKED TO PREVENT RUN OFF. ANOTHER JAS TRANSPORT UNIT ALONG WITH A COMPANY CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO TRANSLOAD THE TRAILER. GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL WAS POTENTIALLY CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF. ADDITIONAL SOIL SAMPLES WERE TESTED BY A & B ENVIRONMENTAL TO ENSURE ALL CONTAMINATION WAS REMOVED FROM THE ACCIDENT SITE. THIS REPORT WAS PROVIDED TO TNRCC. UPON ARRIVING ON SITE, THE CLEAN UP CREW ASCERTAINED THAT THE ' LEAKER ' WAS A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM OF A HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION.  THE REMAINING LIQUID WAS OFFLOADED INTO A 85 GALLON POLY DRUM AND THE IMPACTED PARKING LOT WAS CLEANED.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE SOME TYPE OF PROTRUSION FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR THAT RESULTED IN A LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES STEMMING FROM THE INCIDENT.  A WALK THROUGH OF THE TRAILER PRIOR TO LOADING WOULD BE BENEFICIAL TO ELIMINATE THESE TYPES OF INCIDENTS. E.M.I. # 10450

THIS SHIPMENT WAS PART OF THE AIRCRAFT FREIGHTLOAD OF FEDEX FEEDER FLT-8810.  THIS AIRCRAFT DEPARTED CASPER, WYOMING BOUND FOR STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, COLORADO.  THIS AIRCRAFT CRASHED AT APPROXIMATELY 08:45 (MOUNTAIN TIME) SHORTLY BEFORE REACHING STEAMBOAT SPRINGS.  THE PILOT, KIM KIRKMAN WAS KILLED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  THE DETONATOR SHIPMENT'S OUTER PACKAGE WAS DESTROYED UPON IMPACT ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF 80 UNITS COMMONLY CALLED EXPLOSIVE WELDING PLUGS INTO THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE CRASH. DURING THE SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION OF THE CRASH BY LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND THE NTSB THE UNITS WERE RECOVERED AND PLACED INTO THE CUSTODY OF THE ROUTT COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT (SHERIFF JOHN WARNER) UNTIL A FINAL DISPOSITION OF THE ITEMS CAN BE DETERMINED.  THERE WAS ALSO A SECOND HAZMAT SHIPMENT ONBOARD.  THE SHIPMENT WAS ONE PIECE OF REFRIGERANT GAS, 2.2. UN 1078 AT 35LBS. AB#7924133511721.  THERE WAS NO KNOWN DAMAGE OR RELEASE REGARDING THIS SHIPMENT.  THE REMAINS OF THE CREWMEMBER HAVE BEEN REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND THE REST OF THE FREIGHTLOAD HAD BEEN RECOVERED AND SENT ON THE DESTINATION FEDEX FACILITY (MINUS THE DETONATOR SHIPMENT) FOR FINAL DISTRIBUTION.

A SMALL FIRE STARTED WHEN A PORTION OF THE PRODUCT IGNITED DUE TO THE HEAT WHILE IN THE TRAILER.  THE FIRE WAS QUICKLY EXTINGUISHED AND ALL PRODUCT TO PLACED  IN TO FIBER DRUMS.  THE PACKAGING HAD DETERIORATED ENOUGH AS TO ALLOW THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE INSIDE THE FIBER DRUMS.  THE PRODUCT WOULD MINGLE WITH THE ORGANIC MATERIALS CAUSING A FIRE.  CF HAD NO METAL DRUMS TO PLACE THE PRODUCT INTO.  A REPUTABLE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO THE SITE AND PLACED ALL OF THE MATERIAL INTO METAL DRUMS AND REMOVED THE PRODUCT FROM THE SITE.  NO INJURIES WERE INCURRED.  DUE TO THE REPORTS ON THE STATUS OF THE PACKAGING MATERIAL, THE PRODUCT OWING TO THE DANGERS ASSOCIATED WITH IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN REFUSED.  EMI # 10514

column168: A PASSENGER BAG WAS LEAKING AFTER IT WAS LOADED IN THE AFT BELLY OF THE AIRCRAFT.  THE AFT BELLY MAN SAID THE CARGO HOLD SMELLED OF ALCOHOL.  THE PASSENGER WAS LOCATED AND HE IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE DISINFECTANT SPRAY, WHICH HE HAD INSIDE HIS BAG.  IT APPEARS THAT WHILE LOADING THE BAGS, SOMETHING HIT THE NOZZLE AND RELEASED THE CONTENTS OF A 12-OZ SPRAY CAN.  THE FUMES CAUSED THE CREWMEMBERS IN THE AFT BELLY TO BECOME DIZZY AND LIGHT HEADED.  THEY WENT TO AA MEDICAL BUT WERE RELEASED SHORTLY THEREAFTER.  THE CAN WAS CONFISCATED AND THE PASSENGER WAS EDUCATED ABOUT THE TRANSPORTATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS BY AIR.

column168: DURING THE DOWNLOAD OF SOUTHWEST AIRLINES FLIGHT #574, A RAMP AGENT AT SPOKANE INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (GEG) DISCOVERED A BOX THAT WAS EMITTING A STRONG CHEMICAL ODOR AND THAT HAD LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT.  THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND SEVERAL CHEMICALS WERE DISCOVERED INSIDE.  A SECOND BOX WAS ALSO DISCOVERED, BUT NONE OF THE CONTENTS WERE LEAKING.  THE CUSTOMER WAS NOTIFIED AND THE MATERIALS SEGREGATED.  THE PACKAGE HAD THE CHEMICAL TRADE NAME ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND UPON INSPECTION A PARTIALLY DESTROYED ORM-D LABEL WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TOP OF THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE CONTAINED THE FOLLOWING CHEMICALS:  DESOLVE ODORLESS DRAIN LINE CONTROL (4 BOTTLES AT 2 LBS. EACH)  RE-ACT MALODOR NEUTRALIZER (2 BOTTLES AT 16 OUNCE EACH) CONTROL 7Q NEUTRAL DISINFECTANT CLEANER (1 BOTTLE AT 1 QUART)  CONQUER BIOGRADEABLE EMULSIFIER (1 BOTTLE AT 1 QUART)  BIO-MATIC DRAIN LINE TREATMENT (2 BOTTLES AT 32 OUNCES EACH)  DYNA FOAM OVEN AND GRILL CLEANER (2 BOTTLES AT 32 OUNCES EACH)  ULTRA CHEM INC. MANUFACTURED ALL OF THE CHEMICALS IN THE SHIPMENT.  ALL PRODUCTS WERE PACKAGED IN PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TOPS AND THE CHEMICAL THAT SPILLED WAS NOT ABLE TO BE DETERMINED.  THE CUSTOMER'S MATERIALS WERE RETURNED AFTER THE GEG POLICE DEPARTMENT COMPLETED AN INVESTIGATION (INCLUDING PHOTOGRAPHS) OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE CUSTOMER WAS INFORMED THAT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARE NOT ALLOWED IN CHECKED OR CARRYON BAGGAGE AND THAT HIS MATERIALS WOULD NOT BE ALLOWED ON THE RETURN PORTION OF THIS TRIP.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED THE FOLLOWING MORNING OF THE INCIDENT AND IS CURRENTLY OPENING AN INVESTIGATION.

HOWEVER, A CANISTER OF HOME PEST & CARPET DUST, A PESTICIDE WAS DISCOVERED. THE CANISTER HAD RUPTURED, SPILLING THE DUST OR POWDER INSIDE THE BAG.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ENTIRELY INSIDE THE BAG.
