column168: FILE: 2131 P & D, SHIPPER: GLAXOSMITHKLINE, AWB#: RLE 1963937915 MYR. ON 05/04/2001 A SPILL WAS CALLED INTO THE HAZ MAT DISPATCH ADVISING THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE SMOKING AND HAD AN ACRID ODOR IN BUILDING "D" OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN CARL BOHL AND LORRAINE HARNER RESPONDED. WHILE ENROUTE THEY ADVISED THAT THE IMMEDIATE AREA BE EVACUATED.  10 EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED AND OF THE 10 EMPLOYEES 5 REPORTED THAT THEY WERE IN CONTACT BY INHALATION. UPON ARRIVAL, THE HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS REQUESTED ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE OF ANOTHER SPILL TEAM AND THE HAZ MAT SPILL TEAM SUPERVISOR, BRUCE CUNNINGHAM.  PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED THE AREA AND ONCE ON SCENE THEY PH'D THE LIQUID MATERIAL WHICH GAVE A READING OF "0" INDICATING A VERY STRONG ACID.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THEY FOUND A GLASS OF RECEPTACLES AND THE BROKEN GLASS RECEPTACLE WAS IDENTIFIED AS "HYDROCHLORIC ACID" THE OTHER 3 GLASS RECEPTACLES CONTAINED NON REGULATED PRODUCT, WHICH WILL BE ITEMIZED BELOW.  ALSO FOUND INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID EACH AND EACH OF THE INNER PRODUCT HAD THEIR OWN INDIVIDUAL SAMPLE SUBMISSION FORM REQUESTING SPECIFIC TEST TO BE PERFORMED.  THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO TWO PLASTIC BAGS AND FURTHER PLACED INTO A LINED DOT SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM AND TAKEN TO OUR HAZ MAT SORT BUILDING AND LOCK UP IN OUR SECURITY CAGE PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  ITEMIZED LIST OF INNER CONTENTS ARE AS FOLLOWS:  1 X 100ML GLASS RECEPTACLE OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID (GLASS BROKE, ENTIRE CONTENTS LOST)  1 X 100ML GLASS RECEPTACLE OF OLEIC ACID PRIOLENE (NON-REGULATED)  1 X 40G GLASS RECEPTACLE OF POLYEHTYLENE GLYCOL (NON-REGULATED)  1 X 8G GLASS RECEPTACLE OF SACCHARIN SODIUM (NON-REGULATED)  NONE OF THE EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT BY SMELLING THE ODOR REQUIRED MEDICAL TREATMENT, AND RETURNED TO THEIR ASSIGNED WORK AREAS ONCE THE HAZ MAT SPILL TEAMS CLEANED THE SCENE.  CLEAR OF SCENE 01:02 A.M.

FILE: 3070 D, SHPR.: VWR SCIENTIFIC PRODUCTS, AWB# BVR 06701288593 TRY ON 05/03/2001 AT 01:13 A.M., A LEAKING PACKAGE WAS REPORTED IN A LOWER BELLY COMPARTMENT (BELLY 2) OF ONE OF OUR DC-8 AIRCRAFT AT GATE B-72 OF OUR SORT OF HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED LEAKING WHILE 4 ABX AIR, INC, EMPLOYEES WERE UNLOADING THIS COMPARTMENT AND THAT THEY HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH THE MATERIAL GETTING IT ON THEIR HANDS AND CLOTHING.  UPON ARRIVAL HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS BRUCE SHILTZ AND DIANE RAMSDEN IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING PACKAGE AND NOTICED THAT IT WAS LABELED AS (TOXIC).  THE HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS BACKED AWAY AND BEGAN DONNING THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  THE HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS REMOVED THE LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT FROM THE BELLY COMPARTMENT AND PLACED IT IN DOUBLE BAGS AND THEN INTO A DOT SPECIFICATION STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THEY THEN BEGAN DECONNING THE BELLY COMPARTMENT AND BAGGING AFFECTED REGULAR FREIGHT FOR REPACKING.  THEY HAD CONTACTED OUR ARFF (AIR RESCUE FIRE FIGHTERS) TO RESPOND AND TO EXAMINE THE EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT, WHICH 3 OF THE 4 WERE SHOWING SIGNS OF A REACTION TO THE LEAKING MATERIAL.  THE EMPLOYEES AFFECTED CLOTHING WAS REMOVED AND DECONNED BEFORE RETURNING BACK TO THEM.  THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED AS FOLLOWS: THE INNER 4 LITER CAPACITY GLASS BOTTLE CONTAINING 1 LITER OF THE MATERIAL WAS INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG FILLED WITH A PACKING MATERIAL (VERMICULITE) THEN FURTHER HAD BEEN PLACED IN A THICK POLY LINER BAG AND TIED AT THE TOP IN A KNOT.  THIS WAS HOW IT WAS PACKAGED BEFORE THE SHIPPER PLACED IT IN A FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, PACKAGED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND WAS ACCOMPANIED BY THE APPROPRIATE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS PREPARED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE IATA/ICAO REGULATIONS.  ONCE THE SHIPMENT WAS DRUMMED THE PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS WERE REPRODUCED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO IT'S FINAL DESIGNATED DESTINATION.  THE EMPLOYEES THAT WERE ATTENDED BY CERTIFIED EMT'S WERE RELEASED AND RETURNED BACK TO THEIR ASSIGNED DUTIES AND NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP WAS REQUIRED.  CLEAR OF SCENE 02:06

column168: WHILE UNLOADING GASOLINE (GRAVITY DROP) AT THE CROWN STATION APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLED FROM THE FILL CONNECTION ONTO THE ASPHALT DRIVE. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY THE DRIVER'S FAILURE TO HAVE THE UNLOADING ELBOW (FITTING) PROPERLY SECURED TO THE UNDERGROUND TANK FILL CONNECTION. UPON ELBOW (FITTING) PROPERLY SECURED TO THE UNDERGROUND TANK FILL CONNECTION. UPON DETECTION, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE RELEASE BY CLOSING EMERGENCY VALVES ON THE TANK TRAILER AND PROCEEDED INITIATE CLEANUP, THE FAIRFAX COUNTY FD RESPONDED AND ASSISTED WITH THE CLEANUP. LEESBURG PIKE WAS SHUTDOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY 2.5 HOURS AND TRAFFIC WAS RE-ROUTED THROUGH AN ADJACENT SHOPPING CENTER. FEDERAL (NRC REPORT#567455) AND STATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED. A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF GASOLINE ENTERED A STORM SEWER. THE GASOLINE AND STANDING WATER WAS RECOVERED FROM THE STORM SEWER BY AT A ENVIRONMENTAL. CAUSE: DRIVER FAILED TO SECURE FITTING BEFORE INITIATING THE UNLOADING PROCESS. DRIVER TO RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING

column168: DURING THE TRANSPORTATION OF WHITE LIQUOR FROM SHIPPER TO THE CONSIGNEE, THE DRIVER WAS ON I-55 SOUTH BOUND AND TRANSITIONED ONTO HWY. 24 WEST BOUND AND CONTINUED APPROXIMATELY .25 MILES WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED WHAT APPEARED TO LEAKAGE FROM UNDERNEATH THE TANKER OF THE TRANSPORT CARGO TANK. AT THIS POINT IT WAS TOO LATE TO TURN INTO A NEARBY BP TRUCKSTOP LOCATED ON HWY . 24 WEST DRIVER CONTINUED ON FOR APPROXIMATELY 1.5 MILES UNTIL AT THE INTERSECTION OF HWY .24 AND 48 HE WAS ABLE TO TURN AROUND AND RETURN TO THE BP TRUCKSTOP. IN THE TURNING AROUND PROCESS, LEAKING WHITE LIQUOR WAS RELEASED ONTO HWY 24. THE WHITE LIQUOR WAS ALSO RELEASED ONTO THE PARKING LOT OF THE BP TRUCKSTOP. THE DRIVER LOCATED AN AREA IN THE BACK PORTION OF THE PROPERTY WHICH THE DRIVER THOUGHT WAS SUITABLE TO STOP THE TRUCK AND GET ASSISTANCE FROM LOCAL AUTHORITIES. WITH ASSISTANCE FROM THE MCCOMB POLICE,  FIRE AND PIKE COUNTY CIVIL DEFENSE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A VALVE HAD FAILED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE. THE INITIAL AREA IN WHICH THE TANK WAS FIRST STOPPED WAS UNABLE TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND WITH THE PERMISSION OF THE MISSISSIPPI DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (MDEQ) EMERGENCY SERVICES BRANCH, MR. RICHARD COGHLAN, PIKE COUNTY CIVIL DEFENSE HAD THE TANK MOVED INTO A GRAVEL PIT WHERE THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD RELEASED. THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF THE RELEASE WAS 5000 GALLONS, OF WHICH 3000 GALLONS WAS ABLE TO BE RECOVERED.AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FROM IMC CORPORATION WAS CALLED TO EVALUATE CONTAIN THE SPILL, AND DO THE CLEAN UP THE SPILL SITE. THE PRODUCT RELEASED ONTO HWY. 24 WAS NEUTRALIZED BY IMC AND DEEMED ACCEPTABLE BY MISSISSIPPI DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (MDOT) DISTRICT 7. SOIL FROM THE INITIAL SPILL AREA AND IMPACTED SOIL DOWN SLOPE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DUG UP BY IMC AND PLACED INTO A TREATMENT CELL TO BE NEUTRALIZED. THE NEUTRALIZATION PROCESS WAS PERFORMED BY IMC PERSONNEL AND OBSERVED BY MR. SHANNON LOWERY OF MDEQ, EMERGENCY SERVICES BRANCH. EARTH CON CONSULTING GROUP WAS CALLED AS A THIRD PARTY TO DO THE ANALYTICAL TESTING OF ALL AREAS IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. IMC WITH THIS INFORMATION PROFILED THE SOIL INTO A NON-HAZARDOUS LANDFILL. THE SOIL HAS SINCE BEEN HAULED TO THE LANDFILL AND DISPOSED OF. EARTH CON WILL PROVIDE THE RESULTS OF ALL SAMPLING AND EACH AFFECTED PARTY WILL BE GIVEN A COPY OF SAID FINDINGS. THE CARGO TANK WAS RETURNED TO ITS TERMINAL WHERE AN INSPECTION WAS DONE TO FIND THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE HAD BEEN DEBRIS CAUGHT IN THE INTERNAL VALVE BODY SEAT, WHICH PREVENTED THE VALVE FROM CLOSING COMPLETELY. THIS ALLOWED PRODUCT TO FLOW INTO EXTERNAL PIPING WHICH WAS INCOMPATIBLE WITH THE PRODUCT CAUSING FAILURE OF THE PIPING AND SPILLAGE. THE VALVES AND PIPING WERE ALL REMOVED AND INSPECTED AND REPLACED WITH COMPATIBLE MATERIALS. ALL TANKS IN THIS SERVICE WERE REINSPECTED TO PREVENT THIS TYPE INCIDENT FROM HAPPENING AGAIN. EMPLOYEES WERE INFORMED THAT IF BELIEVE OR SUSPECT THAT THERE MIGHT BE A PROBLEM WITH THEIR VALVE

column168: FILE: 3075 D SHIPPER: REFINISHER'S WAREHOUSE, AWB# WPO 3870582823 QQQ. ON 5/22/2001, AN ODOR WAS CALLED IN TO OUR HAZ MAT DISPATCH THAT THERE WAS A SHIPMENT EMITTING AND ODOR OF PAINT ON LINE 3 IN BUILDING 208 OF OUR HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO, 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS BRUCE SHILTZ AND CECILIA HICKEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED THE AREA.  THE SHIPMENT WAS QUICKLY IDENTIFIED AND THE SPILL TEAM OPENED THE PACKAGE TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR SINCE THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE.  ONCE THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED THE SPILL TEAM DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A METAL CAN INSIDE A THICK PLASTIC BAG WHICH SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  CLOSER EXAMINATION OF THE INNER METAL CAN REVEALED THAT THE CLOSURE WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS, WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE LEAKAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THAT AREA  AND PLACED IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD AND FURTHER PLACED INTO A DOT SPECIFICATION 1A1 DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION ACCOMPANIED THE SHIPMENT DURING TRANSPORT THE PERSON WHO CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE SHIPMENT BY INHALATION ONLY WAS ADVISED OF WHAT THE SPILL WAS AND THE RETURNED TO THEIR NORMAL WORK DUTIES.  THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT REQUIRE ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION AND RETURNED TO WORK.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO IT'S FINAL DESTINATION. THERE ARE DIGITAL PHOTOS ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE. CLEAR OF SCENE: 03:30 A.M.

FILE:3072 D, SHIPPER: ACROS ORGANICS, AWB# EDS 62891300673 PHO & EDS 62891300776 PHO ON 05/09/2001, A CALL CAME IN THAT THERE WAS A SHIPMENT LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR IN OUR HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY, LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  THE CALLER ADVISED THAT ONE EMPLOYEE WAS IN CONTACT BY INHALATION ONLY.  THE EMPLOYEE HAD MINIMAL EXPOSURE DUE TO THEIR VERY BRIEF PRESENTS IN THE AREA.  THIS BUILDING HAD ALL THE DOORS OPEN AND HIGH CEILINGS, EXHAUST FANS UPON ARRIVAL P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS, MICHAEL COOK AND BRUCE SHILTZ EXAMINED THE 3 STEEL DRUMS AND FOUND THAT EACH HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 10 OUNCES OF THEIR CONTENTS DUE TO SEAL FAILURE AROUND THE CLOSURE AND POSSIBLY DUE TO THE SHIPPER OVERFILLING THEM AND THERE NOT BEING ENOUGH OUTAGE TO ALLOW THE MATERIAL TO PROPERLY EXPAND DURING TRANSPORT.  THE THREE SHIPMENTS WERE QUICKLY REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND EACH WERE PLACED INTO ONE 86 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.  THESE THREE SHIPMENTS WERE ALL GOING TO THE SAME CONSIGNEE AND WERE PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND EACH WAS ACCOMPANIED BY THEIR OWN SEPARATE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS. THE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WAS ADVISED WHAT THE MATERIAL WAS AND THAT DUE TO THEIR MINIMAL EXPOSURE MEDICAL FOLLOW-UP WOULD NOT BE NECESSARY.  THE EMPLOYEE RETURNED TO HER NORMAL WORK AREA AND DID NOT MISS ANY WORK TIME. CLEAR OF SCENE: 00:56

ON MAY 19, 2001, ROBERT BECK, A TRANSPORT DRIVER FOR BUTTON TRANSPORTATION, INC. WAS TRANSFERRING APPROXIMATELY 7510 GALLONS OF LIQUIFIED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM A BUTTON TRANSPORTATION'S MC330 CYLINDER OWNED AND OPERATED BY HELENA CHEMICAL COMPANY.  DURING THE UNLOADING TRANSFER PROCESS INTO THE "A" UNIT (FRONT MC330 CYLINDER) AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN AN EMPLOYEE, ROBERT BECK, ACCIDENTALLY OVERFILLED THE CUSTOMERS CYLINDER DUE TO MATHEMATICAL ERROR IN DETERMINING THE 85% TOTAL CAPACITY OF THE "A" UNIT (MC330 CYLINDER).  THE DOMING OF THE CUSTOMER'S CYLINDER CAUSED THE LIQUID ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TO SPILL INTO THE VAPOR LINE FREEZING THE VAPOR COMPRESSION PUMP ON THE SIDE OF BUTTON TRANSPORTATION'S TRANSPORT VEHICLE, CAUSING THE HEAD GASKET TO LEAK, RESULTING IN THE UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 5 GALLONS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WHICH VENTED DIRECTLY INTO THE ATMOSPHERE THROUGH THE VAPOR COMPRESSION PUMP. IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INITIAL DISCHARGE , OUR DRIVER ROBERT BECK WAS ABLE TO IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN ALL AUXILIARY POWER TO THE VAPOR PUMP COMPRESSION AND CLOSE ALL VALVES ON BOTH THE CUSTOMER'S MC330 CYLINDER AND BUTTON TRANSPORTATION'S MC330 CYLINDER.  BOTH CYLINDERS WERE PLACED OUT OF SERVICE, INSPECTED AND RELEASED BACK TO THE APPROPRIATE TERMINALS AFTER MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR INTEGRITY PROBLEMS WERE FOUND.  BUTTON TRANSPORTATION HAS REVIEWED THE INCIDENT AND MODIFIED THEIR TRAINING PROGRAM TO INCLUDE EVEN TOUGHER EDUCATIONAL STANDARD BY INCREASING TRAINING AND TESTING IN BOTH THE CLASSROOM AND ON THE ROAD TRAINING PROGRAMS.

ON MAY 15, 2001 AT 11:39 A.M. A ROSEN'S OPERATED STRAIGHT TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN A COLLISION WITH A PICKUP AT THE INTERSECTION OF US 31 AND COUNTY ROAD 1350. THE  PICKUP OPERATED BY ROCKY LYKE OF MEXICO, INDIANA DID NOT YIELD WHERE A YIELD SIGN WAS POSTED AND PROCEEDED INTO THE PATH OF THE ROSEN TRUCK. MR LYKE WAS SERIOUSLY INJURED AND HOSPITALIZED. THE TRAFFIC WAS STOPPED ON US 31 FOR A PERIOD OF TIME. THERE WAS A 110 GALLON CONTAINER OF TENKOZ 638 ( MANUFACTURED BY ALBAUGH) 2.4-D THAT TIPPED OVER BECAUSE OF THE COLLISION. A SMALL QUANTITY (LESS THAN A GALLON) WAS SPILLED FROM THE CONTAINER. THE MIAMI COUNTY LEPC DIRECTOR, MIKE PECONGA, INDICATED WE NEED TO CLEAN UP THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLED PRODUCT THE MORNING OF MAY 16, 2001. WE WERE CONTACTED BY MIKE PECONGA EARLY THE MORNING OF MAY 16, 2001 AND TOLD THERE WAS NO REASON TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL, BECAUSE THE RAIN THE NIGHT OF MAY 15,2001  HAD DISSIPATED THE SPILL, AND MADE IT IMPOSSIBLE TO CLEAN UP. AFTER REVIEWING THE  INCIDENT THERE APPEARS TO BE NOTHING ROSEN'S INC. COULD HAVE DONE TO PREVENT THE SPILL. THE IMPACT OF THE COLLISION CAUSED THE CONTAINER (WHICH WAS SECURED) TO TIP CAUSING A SMALL RELEASE. WE ARE ATTACHING COPIES OF THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS, MSDS SHEETS AND COPY OF THE ACCIDENT REPORT.

THIS SPILL HAPPENED AT THE FEDEX FBGA STATION WHILE THE MORNING LOADING OPERATION WAS BEING DONE.  3 EMPLOYEES GOT SOME OF THE POWDER ON THEIR HANDS WHERE IT STARTED BURNING THE SKIN.  WHEN THEY WASHED THEIR HANDS, IT TURNED SLIMEY.  ONE EMPLOYEE WENT TO THE DOCTOR BUT WAS CLEARED AFTER A SHORT EXAMINATION.  CLEANUP OF THIS SPILL WAS DONE PER FEDEX POLICY BY THE STATION'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST.  THIS PACKAGE WAS SENT BY AN INDIVIDUAL FROM A NON-FEDEX SHIPPING CENTER.  SINCE THE SHIPPER WOULD NOT BE RESPOND TO PHONE CALLS, THERE WAS NO PHONE NUMBER FOR THE CONSIGNEE AND "HWY 62" WAS NOT A DELIVERABLE ADDRESS, THE LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY WAS CONTACTED.  I NOTIFIED DENNIS KRAUS WITH THE FAA, SINCE THIS MAY BE A UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  AFTER THE FAA LOOKED AT THIS PACKAGE, THE DAVIDSON COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPT TOOK THE PACKAGE INTO THEIR POSSESSION TO BE ANALYZED BY THE STATE CRIME LAB(DAVIDSON COUNTY IS THE CONSIGNEE'S COUNTY).  THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS GIVEN TO FEDEX.  THERE WAS NO MSDS INFORMATION AVAILABLE AND THE ONLY INFORMATION IN THE PACKAGE WAS A NOTE THAT SAID:  "CALL ME TO FIND OUT HOW TO USE THIS".  THIS PACKAGE ALSO CONTAINED A 240 ML CONTAINER OF AN UNKNOWN CLEAR LIQUID.  CURRENTLY, THE STATE LAB HAS NOT IDENTIFIED THIS MATERIAL, THEREFORE CLASSIFICATION OF THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS IS BASED ON CONTACT TO SKIN

THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED BOX HAD TRAVELED FROM TUSCON TO THE PHOENIX RAMP BY TRUCK, FOR PLANNED MOVEMENT ON THE AIRCRAFT ON THIS NIGHT.  DURING FLIGHT PREPARATIONS, AN EMPLOYEE NOTICED A CONTAINER WITH SMOKE INSIDE. THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WERE ALERTED.  UPON OPENING THE CONTAINER, THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE CAUGHT FIRE. THE CONTENTS INSIDE THE PACKAGE HAD BURNED, BUT NOTHING ELSE IN THE CONTAINER WAS EFFECTED.  THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK ASSOCIATED WITH THIS SHIPMENT AND CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE IN TRYING TO IDENTIFY THE COMMODITY.  ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER WITHOUT SUCCESS, SO THE CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED.  THE FAA WAS CONTACTED REGARDING THIS INCIDENT AND ROY MORALES WAS TO INVESTIGATE.  AFTER NUMEROUS CALLS ON 5-14, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SHIPPER.  SLDDCO, WAS RETURNING THE PRODUCT TO PHARMA CORE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION.

column168: ON MAY 25, 2001 CORE LABORATORIES, HOUSTON TX OFFERED TO FEDEX EXPRESS A PACKAGE OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE, LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED UNDER THE PROVISIONS OF 49CFR 173.421 (SEE ATTACHED DRAWING) THE SHIPMENT WAS ADDRESSED TO PROTECHNICS, MIDLAND TEXAS, FOR SATURDAY  DELIVERY/HOLD AT LOCATION (FOR PICKUP).  ON 5/25 THE PACKAGE WAS TRUCKED FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION TO THE FEDEX HOUSTON RAMP. THE PACKAGE THEN LEFT HOUSTON FOR MEMPHIS ON FLIGHT 1211.  UPON ARRIVAL IN MEMPHIS, THE PACKAGE ENTERED THE SORT SYSTEM AND LEFT MEMPHIS ON 5/26 FOR LUBBOCK TEXAS RAMP ON FLIGHT 2408.  UPON ARRIVAL IN LUBBOCK, THE AIRCRAFT WAS UNLOADED, AND THIS PACKAGE CONTINUED ON TO THE MIDLAND TX ONBOARD FEDEX FLIGHT FEEDER 8757.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AT THE MIDLAND RAMP LOCATION FOR PICKUP BY THE RECIPIENT ON SATURDAY MAY 26.  LATER, UPON INSPECTION, THE RECIPIENT REPORTED THE RADIOACTIVE SOURCE TO BE MISSING: A SOLID DISK OF BA-133, 1MCI FEDEX WAS NOTIFIED OF THE MISSING SOURCE ON TUESDAY, MAY 29. STATE AND FEDERAL RADIOLOGICAL AGENCIES WERE ALSO NOTIFIED AT THIS TIME. BEGINNING ON MAY 30, THE POSSIBILITY THAT THE SOURCE CONTAINER WAS NOT PROPERLY SEALED EXISTS.  THE RECIPIENT, PROTECHNICS, CONDUCTED SEARCHES AT THE TEXAS LOCATIONS (HOUSTON, LUBBOCK AND MIDLAND) IN AN ATTEMPT TO LOCATE THE SOURCE.  MEMPHIS SAFETY SEARCHED THE MEM HUB.  THE SOURCE WAS NEVER LOCATED. AWB# 791570063112

AT 1445 HRS ON 5-13-01, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER.  THEY ADVISED THAT THE SETTEGAST YARDMASTER HAD REPORTED LOADED TANK RPBX 235322 TO BE  LEAKING AND THAT CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED IN TRACK 15. UPON ARRIVAL AT CAR LOCATION, MGR LERCH NOTED THE LEFT AND RIGHT SIDES OF THE CAR TO BE MOIST WITH PRODUCT.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT SOURCE OF RELEASE WAS FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, HOWEVER CAUSE OF VALVE OPERATING IS UNKNOWN.  MGR LERCH VENTED CAR, OPENED THE MAN WAY TO DETERMINE IF CAR WAS OVERLOADED.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS SUFFICIENT OUTAGE TO ALLOW FOR EXPANSION OF PRODUCT. UPON DETERMINING THAT THE CAR WAS STABLE AND THAT THERE WE WOULD BE NO FURTHER RELEASE, MGR LERCH NEUTRALIZED CAR WITH A SODIUM BICARBONATE WATER SOLUTION.  CAR WAS THEN PROTECTED TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER MOVEMENT, AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO RESPOND THE FOLLOWING DAY TO REPLACE THE PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE. AT 0900 HRS ON 5-14-01, ROBERT GARCIA, SAFETY SUPERVISOR FROM RHONE POULENC RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, WHICH SECURED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE CAR WAS THEN RE-BILLED BACK TO ITS ORIGINAL LOADING FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION, AND A PRESSURE TEST. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: LANE A SEKAVEC, MANAGER-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN HUTCHINSON, KS.  HE MADE CONTACT WITH MTO TOM SADER, WHO ADVISED MR. SEKAVEC THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE DOME AREA AND EVAPORATING BEFORE REACHING THE GROUND.  MR SEKAVEC ARRANGED TO HAVE HAZ-MAT RESPONSE  RESPOND TO CHECK THE CAR.  AFTER THE CONTRACTOR'S ARRIVAL AND ASSESSMENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PLUG IN THE SAMPLE VALVE WAS NOT IN PLACE.  FURTHER, THE SAMPLE VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE IN THAT PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING EVEN WITH THE VALVE CLOSED.  HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL REPLACED THE PLUG AND SECURED THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT TOPEKA, KS.  THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHILE BEING MOVED.  THE CAR WAS PLACED IN A SECURE LOCATION AND NOT DISTURBED.  EXAMINATION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT ONE OF THE NUTS SECURING THE LIQUID VALVE BODY WAS APPROXIMATELY ONE INCH ABOVE THE FLANGE FOR THE VALVE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE BETWEEN THE FLANGE ON THE TANK CAR AND THE FLANGE ON THE VALVE BODY.  THE VALVE WAS REMOVED, THE GASKET CHECKED, AND THE VALVE SECURELY REINSTALLED.  THE CAR WAS THEN SHAKEN BY A SWITCH ENGINE TO VERIFY THAT THERE WERE NO LEAKS FROM THE REPAIRED VALVE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL UNDER THE CAR WAS DUG UP AND PLACED INTO BARRELS FOR DISPOSAL.  SAMPLES WERE TAKEN OF THE SOIL FOR ANALYSIS.  SAMPLES OF THE GROUND WERE ALSO TAKEN TO VERIFY THAT ALL OF THE CONTAMINATION HAD BEEN REMOVED.

column14: SW MURRAY BLVD & SW BEARD ROAD
column168: ON THE MORNING OF MAY 24, 2001, EMPLOYEES AT THE LOWE'S RETAIL STORE IN TIGARD, OREGON LOADED TRUCKS FILLED WITH PLANTS, PVC PIPE AND CEMENT BLOCK TO BE DELIVERED TO THE OPRAH WINFREY SHOW THAT WAS FILMING IN BEAVERTON, OREGON. TWO TRUCKS WERE FILLED: A TANDEM TRUCK FILLED WITH CEMENT BLOCK AND FOUR PALLETS OF LARGE PLANTS AND A BOX TRUCK/VAN WHICH WAS FILLED WITH MURIATIC ACID WAS ALSO ON THE BOX TRUCK, BUT NO ONE ADMITS TO LOADING THE MURIATIC ACID NOR DO THEY KNOW WHY IT WAS ON THE TRUCK OR WHO PLACED IT THERE. THE OCCUPANTS OF THE TANDEM TRUCK WERE MARK MORIARTY, ASST. STORE MGR.; TOM JONES, DEPT. MANAGER-DELIVERY; AND LUKE PFAENDLER, EMPLOYEE IN THE LOADING/DELIVERY AREA; BRAD HOPE, DEPT. MANAGER-RECEIVING; AND MARK WEEKS, ASST. DEPT. MANAGER-OUTSIDE LAWN & GARDEN. THE TRUCKS PROCEEDED TO LEAVE THE STORE TO MAKE THE DELIVERY. THE BOX TRUCK FOLLOWED BEHIND THE TANDEM TRUCK. NEAR THE DESTINATION POINT, AT THE INTERSECTION OF MURRAY BOULEVARD AND BEARD ROAD, THE TRUCKS MADE A LEFT. THE OCCUPANTS OF THE TANDEM TRUCK, WHICH WAS THE LEAD TRUCK, NOTICED THAT THE BOX TRUCK HAD LOST SOME OF ITS CONTENTS. AFTER BOTH TRUCKS PULLED OFF TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD, TOM JONES RAN BACK TO DETERMINE WHAT OBJECTS FELL OUT OF THE BOX TRUCK AND DETERMINED THAT IT WAS ONE PLANT AND A PLASTIC JUG. BEFORE TOM JONES COULD SAFELY REACH THE JUG A COUPLE OF CARS HIT THE JUG WHICH CAUSED IT TO ROLL AND BECOME PUNCTURED. THEN ANOTHER CAR RAN OVER THE JUG AND IT RUPTURED. TOM JONES INFORMED ALL OF THE OCCUPANTS OF BOTH TRUCKS THAT THERE WAS A HAZMAT SPILL. BOTH TRUCKS PROCEEDED TO MAKE THE DELIVERY AT THE OPRAH WINFREY SET. DURING THIS TIME, CHARLIE WIDENER, LOSS PREVENTION MANAGER AT THE TIGARD, OREGON LOWE'S STORE RECEIVED A CALL FROM LT. AARON GREGG FROM THE TUALATIN VALLEY FIRE AND RESCUE DIVISION WHO NOTIFIED HIM OF THE SPILL. AN EMERGENCY CREW WAS SENT OUT TO THE SITE. MURIATIC ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED USING KOLORSAFE LIQUID NEUTRALIZER. UPON RETURNING TO THE STORE, TOM JONES INFORMED CHARLIE WIDENER OF WHAT HAD TAKEN PLACE AND CHARLIE INFORMED TOM THAT HE WAS AWARE OF IT AND A CLEANUP CREW HAD BEEN DISPATCHED. ON THE SAME DAY, MAY 24, 2001 MARK MORIARTY WAS TERMINATED AND TOM JONES WAS WRITTEN UP AND RECEIVED A FINAL WARNING. ON JUNE 1, 2001 THE FIRE CHIEF OF THE TUALATIN VALLEY FIRE AND RESCUE DEPT. SENT A LETTER TO THE TIGARD, OREGON STORE COMMENDING IT ON THE ACTIONS IT TOOK REGARDING THE SPILL.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE ICTF. DEVELOPED INFORMATION FROM THE ICTF SECURITY FORCES, THAT THEY HAD INSPECTED AN INBOUND (WESTBOUND) TRAIN ON TRACK 808, AND NOTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM A FLAT CAR, DTTE 62022, THAT CONTAINED 4 INTERMODAL TANKS, ALL WERE PLACARDED COMMODITIES. THEY DID NOT SEE ANY VISIBLE SIGNES OF LEAKAGE TO DETERMINE WHICH TANK MIGHT BE THE LEAKER. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF, LOCATED THE THE FLAT CAR WITH THE IM TANKS, AND SUSPECTED THE ABOVE TANK AS THE LEAKER BASED UPON THE ODORS. AFTER DONNING THE APPROPREATE PPE, INSPECTED THE TOP OF THE IM TANK AND FOUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LOOSE PRODUCT IN THE MANWAY SPILL BOX AREA. SIX OF THE EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE EASILY TURNED. THE MANWAY GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. THE MANWAY WAS RESECURED AND PROPERLY TIGHTENED. THE RESIDUE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SPILL BOX AND THE IM TANK RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

column168: ENOTRADE, INC. DRIVER MUHAMED KAMBEROVIC WAS DRIVING ON I-85 SOUTH AND EXITED RIGHT AT EXIT 147, ONTO THE OFF-RAMP. AT THAT TIME HE HEARD A LOUD NOISE IN THE TRAILER AND THE TRAILER STARTED TO WEAVE. AFTER APPROXIMATELY 60 YARDS HE LOST CONTROL AND THE TRAILER TURNED OVER ON IT'S LEFT SIDE. THIS HAPPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 PM ON SATURDAY, MAY 19, 2001. ENOTRADE RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE GEORGIA STATE PATROL AROUND 6:30 PM NOTIFYING THE COMPANY ABOUT THE ACCIDENT. ENOTRADE THEN SPOKE TO MIKE TAYLOR OF THE EPA AND MIKE DERRICK OF DNR. THEY ADVISED THAT THEY WERE PROCEEDING TO CLEAN UP THE AREA AND ASKED ENOTRADE TO HIRE AN OUTSIDE PRIVATE FIRM TO HELP WITH THE SITUATION. ENOTRADE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED AND AUTHORIZED HEPACO, INC TO HELP CLEAN UP THE SPILL. HEPACO'S CREW WAS DISPATCHED AND TOOK OVER THE JOB OF CLEANING UP THE SPILL. TO PREVENT EVENTS OF THIS MAGNITUDE FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE, AND IN LIGHT OF THE CURRENT WORLD CIRCUMSTANCES, ENOTRADE HAS STOPPED TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FURTHERMORE, THE COMPANY HAS INCREASED IT'S SAFETY MEASURES BY ORDERING MANDATORY DRIVER TESTS CONCERNING SAFETY ISSUES, ROADSIDE INSPECTIONS AND MAINTENANCE. A MONTHLY TRANSPORTATION SAFETY TRAINING NEWSLETTER HAS ALSO BEEN SUBSCRIBED TO AND USED. THE STUDY MATERIALS, TESTS, AND NEWSLETTER WERE OBTAINED FROM JJ KELLER & ASSOCIATES.

column168: ON 05/10/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30PM NMM ENTERPRISES, INC HAD A SPILL ON SITE.  THE TRAILER VALVES ON OUR TRAILER UNIT #1088 MALFUNCTIONED CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 800 GALLONS OF 6 OIL PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  I. DAVID DUPRIEST WAS UNLOADING TRAILER 1088 INTO OUR FRAC TANK #2.  THE TRAILER WAS APPROXIMATED 6,500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT IN IT.  I UNLOADED 1/2 OF THE LOAD INTO TANK #2 AND SHUT OFF THE HYDRAULIC VALVE.  I THEN WENT TO THE SCREW TO SWITCH THE HOSE FROM TANK #2 TO TANK #3 SO I COULD UNLOAD THE REMAINDER OF PRODUCT FROM TRAILER 1088 INTO TANK #3.  WHEN I PULLED THE HOSE LOOSE FROM TANK #2 PRODUCT STARTED SPILLING OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  I IMMEDIATELY RAM BACK TO THE TRAILER TO FIGURE OUT WHY THE VALVES WERE NOT HOLDING.  I PUMPED THE HYDRAULIC VALVE SEVERAL TIMES, BUT COULD NOT STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  I THEN WENT TO THE SCREW VALVE TO CHECK IT.  IT WAS CLOSED COMPLETELY BUT THE PRODUCT WAS STILL COMING OUT OF THE HOSE.  I THEN CALLED DAVID KRAMER ON THE RADIO TO COME AND ASSIST ME.  WHEN MR. KRAMER ARRIVED WE DECIDED TO PUT A PLUG IN THE HOSE.  I HELD THE HOSE WHILE MR. KRAMER INSTALLED THE PLUG.  IN THE PROCESS MR. KRAMER SUFFERED BURNS ON BOTH HANDS BECAUSE THE PRODUCT WAS HEATED, BUT IT STOPPED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  ONCE THE PRODUCT FLOW WAS STOPPED WE BEGAN TO CONTAIN THE SPILL BUT WERE UNABLE TO PREVENT THE PRODUCT FROM SPILLING INTO THE DRAINAGE DITCH WHICH BORDERS OUR PROPERTY.  IT WAS AT THIS TIME THAT MR. KRAMER WENT BACK TO THE OFFICE TO REPORT THE SPILL TO THE PROPER AUTHORITIES AND I BEGAN EXAMINING THE VALVE TO SEE WHY IT DID NOT HOLD.  AT THIS TIME I INSTALLED A NEW HYDRAULIC PUMP AT WHICH TIME THE HYDRAULIC VALVE CLOSED PROPERLY.  I THEN DRAINED THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE HOSE AND REMOVED IT FROM TRAILER 1088.  I REMOVED THE SCREW VALVE AND DETERMINED THAT THE TEFLON SEAT AND THE NUT WERE MISSING SO I INSTALLED A NEW VALVE. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30PM GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED AND TOOK OVER THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES.
